{Welcome to my course My First Opening Repertoire: 1.d4! My name is Alex Colovic and I'm a Grandmaster. I am the first Grandmaster on Chessable, having been a regular author on the platform since its beginning. I have had some success as a player and coach, but my biggest ones have been on Chessable, consistently creating best-selling courses. I have also become famous for my simplified approach to openings and in this course I will present you with a simple and straightforward way of developing with the White pieces after the move} 1. d4 {The guiding idea behind this repertoire is to provide the student with a simple, safe and harmonious approach that will lead to smooth development with easily-executable plans to follow up. With simplicity and safety on our minds, I am proposing a set-up that consists of four key moves: Nf3, e3, Be2 and O-O. In most cases these moves can be played automatically and they ensure against any trouble against the white king. Once this set-up is in place, there will be two possible plans afterwards: 1. The continuation of the development with b3 and Bb2, which is followed up with the advance of the c-pawn with c4 and then the queen's knight will either be developed on c3 with Nc3 or on d2 with Nbd2; or 2. A more direct central approach with the move c4 with an attack on the centre (where the moves b3 and Bb2 can be played at a later stage). Generally speaking, White usually will prefer the first plan, unless there is something concrete and the second one is preferable. These situations will be clearly pointed out in the following chapters. As a result of these guidelines, this repertoire will lead to very safe positions where it's impossible to blunder or make a mistake, thus drastically reducing the risk of losing. Throughout the course you will notice several rules of thumb, which will greatly help you to navigate the standard situations that will arise in the course. These rules of thumb are the following:  * 1. Play the move h3 when a black bishop appears on g4;  * 2. After White has played b3, when Black captures a pawn on the d4-square with...cxd4, White should always recapture on d4 with a piece, keeping the long diagonal open for the bishop on b2;  * 3. Capture Black's pawn on c5 with dxc5 only when Black has already moved the dark-squared bishop to e7 or d6, thus forcing it to move again.  * 4. When there is a central confrontation of pawns on the squares c4, d4, c5 and d5, capture the pawn on d5 with cxd5. This in turn will lead to two scenarios:  * a. Black recaptures with a pawn, when White's plan is to place rooks on c1 and e1, with the subsequent relocation of the light-squared bishop to f1, followed by g3 and Bg2, with the idea to solidify the kingside and target the pawn on d5; or  * b. Black recaptures with a piece, when White will either attempt to advance with the e-pawn with e4-e5 or will capture on c5 with dxc5 and open the position in the centre. Now, armed with all of the preparatory remarks, it's time to delve into the concrete variations of the repertoire. Good luck!} *

