1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nc6 {The developing move of the other knight is played quite often. The knight controls the e5-square. It is in the spirit of the Chigorin Defence, where Black's aim is to achieve the ...e5 push.} 3. e3 {White continues with the intended development of Be2 and short castle.} Bf5 {This move is an alternative development of the queen's bishop.} 4. Be2 {White continues with the development of the kingside.} e6 ({In case Black attacks the pawn on c2 with} 4... Nb4 {White calmly defends the pawn with} 5. Na3 {and will then chase away the black knight on b4 with c3.}) 5. O-O {White finished the development of the kingside and is now ready to either expand in the centre with c4 or to develop further by b3 and Bb2.} Nb4 {Black attacks the pawn on c2 and threatens ...Nxc2, winning the rook on a1.} ({If Black develops with} 5... Nf6 {then White expands in the centre with} 6. c4 {followed by Nc3. Now White should defend against Black's threat.}) 6. Na3 {Safely defending the pawn on c2. White will first continue with c3, to chase the knight back, and then with c4, to expand in the centre. The dark-squared bishop will be developed to d2, to support a queenside advance with c5 and b4-b5.} *

