1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nc6 {The developing move of the other knight is played quite often. The knight controls the e5-square. It is in the spirit of the Chigorin Defence, where Black's aim is to achieve the ...e5 push.} 3. e3 {White continues with the intended development of Be2 and short castle.} Bg4 {Black attacks the knight on f3 and plans to expand with ...e5.} ({Developing the other knight with} 3... Nf6 {is analysed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6.}) ({Note that the immediate} 3... e5 $2 {leads to a loss of a pawn after the simple recapture} 4. Nxe5 {.}) ({Black can try to prepare the central advance ...e5 by playing} 3... f6 {, but White is first to attack the centre with} 4. c4 $1 {when after} e5 5. dxe5 fxe5 6. cxd5 {White wins a pawn.}) 4. Be2 {White plays the already-planned move and intends to castle on the next move.} Bxf3 ({By exchanging the knight, Black eliminates a piece that controls the e5-square. The move} 4... Nf6 {is an alternative and is analysed [/variation/44724137/#/4/b] via the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2EndFEN 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 4.Be2 Bg4 .}) ({Another option for Black is to develop with} 4... e6 5. O-O Bd6 {but with the king safe, White can already advance in the centre with} 6. c4 {with Nc3 next.}) 5. Bxf3 {White naturally recaptures the bishop and places the light-squared bishop on the long diagonal.} e5 $2 {This move is a natural continuation after Black's last move - Black expands in the centre by pushing ...e5 after having eliminated the white knight that controlled that square. However, there is a big problem with this move, as we shall see.} ({Better is to play} 5... Nf6 {when White attacks the pawn on d5 with} 6. c4 $1 {intending Qb3, targeting both the pawn on d5 and the pawn on b7. If Black takes the pawn on c4 with} dxc4 {White regains the pawn after} 7. Qa4 {, attacking the knight on c6 and the pawn on c4 at the same time.}) 6. dxe5 {White captures the pawn and now we see the problem with Black's idea - with the d-file opened, the queen joins the bishop in the attack on the pawn on d5. This means that White wins a pawn.} Nxe5 7. Bxd5 {When there is a further attack on the pawn on b7. White is a clear pawn up and Black doesn't have anything to show for it. White will continue development with O-O, Nc3 and then expand with e4.} *

