1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} g6 {Black wants to develop the bishop to g7 ('the fianchetto').} 4. Be2 {White is undisturbed and continues with the standard development.} Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4 ({Since Black has no presence of pieces on the queenside, White can be more ambitious and grab space with this advance instead of the more modest} 6. b3 {, which is perfectly fine, too. Now White's plan in simple, the bishop will come to b2 and then White will expand on the queenside with Nbd2, c4, a4, b5 etc.}) *

