1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} Nc6 {This is a developing move that corresponds to the development principles taught to beginners: first develop the knights, then the bishops.} 4. Be2 {Preparing to get the king to safety.} e6 {By playing this move Black wants to develop the bishop from f8 and castle.} 5. O-O {White continues with the plan of development.} Bd6 {With the bishop on d6 Black has more control of the central e5-square, so the threat is to advance with ...e5.} 6. c4 $1 {It's important for White to start an attack on the black central pawn on d5 and threaten c5 in order to discourage Black's central advance with ...e5.} O-O ({If Black takes the pawn} 6... dxc4 7. Nbd2 $1 {ensures that White will recapture on c4 with a knight, thus controlling the central squares e5 and d6, because defending the pawn with} b5 $2 {runs into} 8. a4 $1 a6 9. axb5 {and Black loses material as} axb5 $2 10. Rxa8 {wins the game for White, being a full rook up now.}) 7. c5 {White grabs space and attacks the bishop on d6.} Be7 8. Bd2 {Preparing to push the b-pawn to attack Black on the queenside. White has the straightforward plan to advance on that side of the board with further b4-b5, a4 etc.} *

