1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} Nc6 {This is a developing move that corresponds to the development principles taught to beginners: first develop the knights, then the bishops.} 4. Be2 {Preparing to get the king to safety.} Bg4 {Black developed the knights and now develops the bishop.} 5. h3 {) It is always useful to play this move: first, it attacks the opponent's bishop and second, after White castles, the king on g1 will always have an escape square on h2, thus never having to worry about mates on the back rank, which can happen out of nowhere in the future.} Bxf3 {Exchanging a bishop for a knight gives White the advantage of the two bishops.} 6. Bxf3 {The bishop on f3 is very strong on the long diagonal.} e5 ({This central advance is more critical. The move} 6... e6 {allows White to finish development in peace and start activity in the centre after} 7. O-O {and c4 next.}) 7. O-O $1 {It's important not to take the pawn on e5 because after 7.dxe5 Nxe5 , Black has very well-placed pieces in the centre, the knight on e5 attacking the bishop on f3 when Black can continue development with ...Bd6 etc. Therefore, White provokes Black's advance in order to be able to counterattack the overextended pawns.} e4 ({Black naturally advances by attacking the bishop on f3. In case of an exchange of pawns after} 7... exd4 8. exd4 {, White has good development after Re1, Nc3, Bf4 or Bg5 and so on.}) 8. Be2 {The bishop escapes the attack. White is now ready to attack Black's pawn on d5 with c4 and Nc3 with good play in the centre, as Black will find it difficult to maintain the defence of the pawn on d5.} *

