1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} Nc6 {This is a developing move that corresponds to the development principles taught to beginners: first develop the knights, then the bishops.} 4. Be2 {Preparing to get the king to safety.} Bg4 {Black developed the knights and now develops the bishop.} 5. h3 {It is always useful to play this move: first, it attacks the opponent's bishop and second, after White castles, the king on g1 will always have an escape square on h2, thus never having to worry about mates on the back rank, which can happen out of nowhere in the future.} Bh5 6. O-O {White finishes the development of the kingside by castling short.} e6 7. c4 {After finishing development White has two plans at their disposal: b3 and Bb2 or c4. In this case White advances in the centre immediately because the pawn on c4 anticipates a development of the black bishop to d6, when the pawn can be used to attack that bishop by advancing further.} Bd6 {This is the most common move, but it plays into White's hands.} ({In case of a pawn capture, White plays} 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bd6 9. Nbd2 {(connecting the knights) when the plan is to return with the bishop back to e2 in order to free the c4-square for the knight, from where it attacks the bishop on d6.}) 8. c5 {This is what White had in mind when starting with the advance of the c-pawn. It is a common idea worth remembering when there is a black bishop on d6.} Be7 9. b4 $1 {White can advance immediately and this sets a small trap. The pawn cannot be taken.} Nxb4 $2 10. Qb3 {The queen attacks the knight on b4, but when the knight moves then the pawn on b7 will fall.} Nc6 11. Qxb7 {Regaining the pawn and continuing the attack on the knight.} Z0 ({Now, if Black is to avoid immediate loss, they should play} 11... Na5 12. Qa6 c6 13. Bd2 Nc4 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. Qxc6+ {when White wins a pawn and remains in a superior position.}) *

