1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c5 {This move is a major alternative. Black plays actively in the centre, but that doesn't bother White as it's perfectly possible to continue with the automatic development undisturbed.} 4. Be2 {One of the reasons for the preference of the development of the bishop to e2 rather than on d3 is that it avoids possible attacks by the black pawn after ...c4. The bishop is safer on e2 and allows White to continue without having to worry about anything.} Nc6 {Black develops the knights first.} 5. O-O {White has completed the development of the kingside. Now Black has a wide choice of plans, but this shouldn't worry White, as in all the cases, except when Black captures on d4, White will continue with one of the plans outlined in the Introduction: b3 and Bb2.} Bg4 {This is a natural move that develops the bishop on an active square.} 6. h3 {The rule of thumb is to always play this move when a bishop appears on g4. It forces Black to determine their intentions what to do with the bishop while at the same time the white king gets an escape square on h2.} Bh5 ({Black keeps both bishops. In case of} 6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 e6 8. c4 {White executes one of the main ideas, here enhanced because of the bishop's control of the light squares in the centre. The point of the move is that the pawn cannot really be taken after} dxc4 9. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 10. Qa4 {thanks to the double attack on the pawns on c6 and c4, White regains the pawn and leaves Black with a crippled pawn structure.}) 7. b3 {After improving the position with the available escape square on h2, White continues with one of the basic plans: b3, with the idea to develop the bishop on b2.} e6 8. Bb2 {White continues with the plan. Now the idea is to open the diagonal for the bishop on b2 by taking on c5 and pushing c4. This can be preceeded by Nbd2, for extra support for the c4 push. What is important to remember is that if Black takes the pawn on d4, White should always keep taking with a piece, in order to keep the long diagonal open. For example after} cxd4 ({If Black doesn't take the pawn and plays} 8... Bd6 {, White will force the black bishop to move again by opening the long diagonal with} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c4 {with either Nc3 or Nbd2 next.}) 9. Nxd4 ({Is the correct recapture, not} 9. exd4 $6 {which would leave the bishop on b2 hitting its own pawn on d4.}) 9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 {Developing the queen.} Bd6 {If Black captures the knight on d4 then White follows the rule of thumb to keep the long diagonal open for the bishop and will recapture with a bishop.} 11. Nd2 {White finished the development of all the pieces and is ready to push c4, with the rooks coming to the d- and c- central files. If Black captures the knight on d4, White will follow the rule of thumb to keep the long diagonal open for the bishop and will recapture with the bishop, again followed by the c4-push.} *

