1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c5 {This move is a major alternative. Black plays actively in the centre, but that doesn't bother White as it's perfectly possible to continue with the automatic development undisturbed.} 4. Be2 {One of the reasons for the preference of the development of the bishop to e2 rather than on d3 is that it avoids possible attacks by the black pawn after ...c4. The bishop is safer on e2 and allows White to continue without having to worry about anything.} Nc6 {Black develops the knights first.} 5. O-O {White has completed the development of the kingside. Now Black has a wide choice of plans, but this shouldn't worry White, as in all the cases, except when Black captures on d4, White will continue with one of the plans outlined in the Introduction: b3 and Bb2.} Bf5 {This is another natural developing move for Black.} 6. b3 ({White continues with one of the basic plans, b3 and Bb2. Note that taking the pawn on c5 doesn't bring much after} 6. dxc5 $6 e6 {and Black will recapture the pawn on c5 with the bishop from f8 in one go, not having wasted tempo by developing it first to e7 or d6. This is an important rule of thumb for White, the capture on c5 makes sense only if it forces Black to lose time by moving the bishop for a second time.}) 6... e6 7. Bb2 {White plays the natural moves.} Be7 ({If Black initiates exchanges in the centre by} 7... cxd4 {then White should remember to keep the long diagonal open and to keep recapturing with a piece, hence} 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 {when White already threatens to disturb the black king with a bishop check from b5.}) 8. dxc5 $1 {The rule of thumb described above in action - White captures the pawn on c5 and opens the long diagonal only after Black had moved the bishop from f8, thus forcing Black to move that bishop again in order to regain the pawn.} Bxc5 9. a3 {A useful move whose aim is to gain space on the queenside by advancing with b4. White always keeps the option to advance with c4, but it would be better if first b4 is played.} a5 ({Black stops the planned advance, but this weakens the b5-square, something White can take advantage of. In case of} 9... O-O 10. b4 Bd6 11. Nbd2 {White will continue with c4 and b5, with active play on the queenside.}) 10. c4 {White will follow up with the development of the knight to c3, when the knight will target the weakened square on b5.} *

