1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c5 {This move is a major alternative. Black plays actively in the centre, but that doesn't bother White as it's perfectly possible to continue with the automatic development undisturbed.} 4. Be2 {One of the reasons for the preference of the development of the bishop to e2 rather than on d3 is that it avoids possible attacks by the black pawn after ...c4. The bishop is safer on e2 and allows White to continue without having to worry about anything.} Nc6 {Black develops the knights first.} 5. O-O {White has completed the development of the kingside. Now Black has a wide choice of plans, but this shouldn't worry White, as in all the cases, except when Black captures on d4, White will continue with one of the plans outlined in the Introduction: b3 and Bb2.} cxd4 {This move leads to the only type of position where White's plan is not b3 and Bb2 or c4.} 6. exd4 {) The structure that is now on the board is called the reversed Carlsbad structure (the Carlsbad structure arises in the Queen's Gambit Declined, Exchange Variation, when it is Black who has the same structure as White in this position). White's set-up in this variation is uniform (as we shall soon see) and in all cases they will start with c3, connecting the structure on the queenside. If White really insists, it is possible to take the pawn with a knight, but without b3, White is not keeping any diagonal open, in addition to the fact that Black can now play ...e5 in one go, making this recapture suboptimal in this case.} Bg4 ({The most common move. In case of} 6... Bf5 {the simplest is to exchange the active bishop after} 7. c3 e6 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 {and follow up with Bg5, Nbd2 and Rfe1 or Rae1. White's plan is to plant a knight on the central square e5 and start an attack on the kingside by various means - with the Re3-g3 rook transfer (h3), by advancing h4-h5-h6, by pushing f4 and/or g4, bringing the other knight to f3 or to g3 via f1 etc. These ideas are applicable in all similar positions, so keep them in mind.}) ({If Black plays the move} 6... e6 {after} 7. c3 {, the position is analysed [/variation/44740757/#/7/w] in the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 cxd4 5.exd4 d5 6.O-O Nc6 7.c3 .}) 7. c3 {This move is a must, so White should play it as soon as possible. It connects the pawn structure and allows for the further smooth development, not having to worry about the pawn on d4 hanging.} e6 8. Bg5 {To keep it consistent with the moves mentioned in the comment on Black's 6th move (6...Bf5 7.c3 e6 8.Bd3) and avoid confusion, White can develop in exactly the same way. Now White wants to finish development by placing the queen's knight on d2. With this being said, it's also possible to develop the bishop to f4.} Be7 9. Nbd2 {White successfully finished development of the whole army.} O-O 10. Bd3 {An important idea. If the light-squared bishops are not exchanged, White wants to place their own on the more active square d3 from where it looks down Black's kingside. White's plan now is to play Re1, placing the rook on the e-file and moving the queen from its initial square to c2 in order to allow for the knight to jump to e5. If White achieves this, all the pieces will be well-placed in the centre and White can use them to start to create threats on the kingside.} *

