1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c5 {This move is a major alternative. Black plays actively in the centre, but that doesn't bother White as it's perfectly possible to continue with the automatic development undisturbed.} 4. Be2 {One of the reasons for the preference of the development of the bishop to e2 rather than on d3 is that it avoids possible attacks by the black pawn after ...c4. The bishop is safer on e2 and allows White to continue without having to worry about anything.} Nc6 {Black develops the knights first.} 5. O-O {White has completed the development of the kingside. Now Black has a wide choice of plans, but this shouldn't worry White, as in all the cases, except when Black captures on d4, White will continue with one of the plans outlined in the Introduction: b3 and Bb2.} e6 {This move is the most commonly played one in this position. Black keeps the light-squared bishop at home and wants to continue with the development of the kingside.} ({Before continuing let's note that Black cannot develop the bishop to g7 after} 5... g6 $6 {as after} 6. dxc5 Bg7 7. Nbd2 {followed by Nb3 White safely defends the extra pawn on c5.}) ({Another not very good move is} 5... c4 $6 {, as it doesn't make sense when there is no bishop to attack on d3. White immediately undermines that pawn with} 6. b3 {and after} cxb3 7. axb3 {White has all the pawns connected and will continue with c4.}) 6. b3 {White's play is very simple, following one of the two main plans. The idea is to develop the bishop on the long diagonal on b2.} Be7 {Black can also develop this bishop on d6, but White's reaction to both is the same and it follows the rule of thumb that once Black moves the dark-squared bishop, White should capture the pawn on c5, forcing that bishop to move again and lose time.} 7. dxc5 $1 {Forcing the bishop to move again in order to regain the pawn.} Bxc5 8. Bb2 {Now White continues the planned development.} O-O 9. a3 {We also saw this useful move in the similar situation arising in the line after 5...Bf5. White plans to expand by pushing the b-pawn, which at the same time would attack the bishop on c5.} Be7 ({The bishop escapes in due time. If Black stops the advance of the white b-pawn by} 9... a5 {, this move weakens the b5-square, something that White can use after} 10. c4 {followed by Nc3, when the knight targets the b5-square.}) 10. Nbd2 {White stays flexible. First we finish development and then depending on Black's replies either b4 or c4 will be played.} Z0 ({A sample line is} 10... b6 11. b4 Bb7 12. Rc1 {followed by c4, with play in the centre. White can use the extra space on the queenside to place the queen on b3 and liberate the d1-square for the king's rook.}) *

