1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c5 {This move is a major alternative. Black plays actively in the centre, but that doesn't bother White as it's perfectly possible to continue with the automatic development undisturbed.} 4. Be2 {One of the reasons for the preference of the development of the bishop to e2 rather than on d3 is that it avoids possible attacks by the black pawn after ...c4. The bishop is safer on e2 and allows White to continue without having to worry about anything.} Nc6 {Black develops the knights first.} 5. O-O {White has completed the development of the kingside. Now Black has a wide choice of plans, but this shouldn't worry White, as in all the cases, except when Black captures on d4, White will continue with one of the plans outlined in the Introduction: b3 and Bb2.} e6 {This move is the most commonly played one in this position. Black keeps the light-squared bishop at home and wants to continue with the development of the kingside.} ({Before continuing let's note that Black cannot develop the bishop to g7 after} 5... g6 $6 {as after} 6. dxc5 Bg7 7. Nbd2 {followed by Nb3 White safely defends the extra pawn on c5.}) ({Another not very good move is} 5... c4 $6 {, as it doesn't make sense when there is no bishop to attack on d3. White immediately undermines that pawn with} 6. b3 {and after} cxb3 7. axb3 {White has all the pawns connected and will continue with c4.}) 6. b3 {White's play is very simple, following one of the two main plans. The idea is to develop the bishop on the long diagonal on b2.} cxd4 {This is commonly played, but White's reaction is a well-known one: White must always recapture on d4 with a piece.} 7. Nxd4 {White keeps the long diagonal open. The plan still remains the same: Bb2 and c4.} Bd6 {Black develops the bishop and plans to castle.} 8. Bb2 {White's play is really simple.} O-O 9. c4 {By playing c4 before the development of the knight White keeps the option to develop it to either to c3 or d2, depending on circumstances. One of White's main strategic ideas in these structures is to capture on d5, with two scenarios: 1. Black recaptures with a knight, in which case White captures the knight on c6, forcing ...bxc6, and leaving Black with an isolated pawn on c6 on the c-file; or 2. Black recaptures with a pawn, in which case Black is saddled with a so-called isolated queen's pawn (IQP) on d5, with White having total control of the blockading d4-square in front of it.} *

