is to develop the bishop on the long diagonal on b2.} cxd4 {This is commonly played, but White's reaction is a well-known one: White must always recapture on d4 with a piece.} 7. Nxd4 {White keeps the long diagonal open. The plan still remains the same: Bb2 and c4.} e5 {Black loses a move, by playing with the same pawn for a second time, but it does attack the knight on d4.} 8. Nxc6 {White naturally escapes with the knight by capturing the opponent's on c6.} bxc6 9. c4 {In spite of the changed central structure, White's plan remains the same - the bishop will come to b2, to target the pawn on e5 and the knight will come to c3, to exert more pressure on the black pawn on d5. In these structures White would like to provoke Black into playing ...e4 (often White would play Bf3 to lure Black to push the pawn) as that would open the long diagonal for the bishop on b2 and will give White complete control of the d4-square.} *

