is to develop the bishop on the long diagonal on b2.} cxd4 {This is commonly played, but White's reaction is a well-known one: White must always recapture on d4 with a piece.} 7. Nxd4 {White keeps the long diagonal open. The plan still remains the same: Bb2 and c4.} Bc5 8. Bb2 {White continues with the usual development.} O-O 9. c4 {White executes the main plan.} dxc4 $6 ({This is not good and Black in fact has several moves that are not good, for example the 'natural'} 9... e5 $2 {loses a pawn to} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxe5 {.}) ({Or} 9... Nxd4 10. exd4 $1 {(an exception to the rule of thumb to keep the long diagonal open is motivated by the fact that White attacks the bishop on c5 and gains space on the queenside)} Be7 11. c5 {with the straightforward plan to push the pawns forward on the queenside.}) ({The best move for Black is the not-so-obvious} 9... Bxd4 $1 10. Bxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 {when White has an active queen and Black still needs to develop the pieces on the queenside.}) 10. Nxc6 $1 {An important capture that wrecks Black's pawns on the queenside.} bxc6 11. Bxc4 {White has the better structure since Black's pawns on a7 and c6 are isolated and weak. White's plan consists of organising an attack against them, primarily using the c-file for the queen and rook. The next moves will be Qc2, Nd2 and Rac1, or if Black exchanges queens then White recaptures with the rook from f1, keeping the other rook to come to c1.} *

