1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c6 {This move is characteristic of the Slav Defence.} 4. Be2 {White continues as usual. Now Black has three types of development: 1. To develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4 before playing ...e6; 2. To play ...e6 immediately; or 3. To play the fianchetto with ...g6 and ...Bg7.} g6 {Black wants to play ...Bg7 and ...O-O. This line is similar to the one arising after 3...g6, so White's plan is the same as in that line:} 5. O-O {First the natural move to get the king to safety.} Bg7 6. b4 ({Second, grabbing queenside space (though there is nothing wrong with} 6. b3 {, White will have to lose time to play b4 later on, but that is fine) and intending to follow up with Bb2, Nbd2, c4, a4, b5 etc. with further expansion. For an example of how to play this position, take a look at the model game Grandelius-Gaehwiler [/variation/44740511].}) *

