1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c6 {This move is characteristic of the Slav Defence.} 4. Be2 {White continues as usual. Now Black has three types of development:  * 1. To develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4 before playing ...e6;  * 2. To play ...e6 immediately; or  * 3. To play the fianchetto with ...g6 and ...Bg7.} e6 {This is the so-called Semi-Slav development. Black keeps the bishop on c8 and speeds up the development of the other pieces.} 5. O-O {White completes the development of the kingside.} Bd6 {Black can also start with 5...Nbd7 and then play ...Bd6, which would lead to the same positions.} 6. b3 {Without a bishop to chase (as in the line after 4...Bf5) White is in no rush to play c4 and Nc3 and can first develop the bishop to b2.} O-O 7. Bb2 {White completes the development of the bishop and will follow up with c4 and Nc3.} Nbd7 8. c4 {The knight will be more active on c3 than on d2, so White first expands in the centre as then the knight can be comfortably placed behind the c-pawn.} Re8 {One of Black's main ideas in the Semi-Slav structures is to execute the ...e5 push. The rook move aids this plan.} ({An alternative is the move} 8... b6 {, with the idea to develop the bishop to b7. White continues with} 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Qc2 {following up with Bd3 and eventually e4 (possibly prepared by the placement of the rooks in the centre on d1 and e1). Take a look at the model game Svane-Orozbaev [/variation/44740512] to see an instructive example of White's play in this position.}) 9. Nc3 {White's plan is to further improve the position of the pieces with Qc2, Bd3, Rad1, Rfe1 and execute the central advance e4.} Z0 ({Note that Black cannot play his preferred plan of} 9... e5 $6 {because in that case White wins a pawn after} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. cxd5 cxd5 {.}) *

