1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c6 {This move is characteristic of the Slav Defence.} 4. Be2 {White continues as usual. Now Black has three types of development:  * 1. To develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4 before playing ...e6;  * 2. To play ...e6 immediately; or  * 3. To play the fianchetto with ...g6 and ...Bg7.} Bf5 {Black doesn't want to end up with a bishop stuck on c8 after e6, so the bishop comes out.} 5. O-O {White's moves are the usual ones.} e6 {Black's standard development in these Slav set-ups is to play ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6.} 6. c4 {White advances in the centre immediately. This is important as White wants to be able to play Nc3 without blocking the pawn on c2.} Bd6 7. Nh4 $1 {The key move for White in this line. The idea is to exchange a knight for the exposed bishop and gain the advantage of the two bishops, which can be used later in the game by opening the position and giving the bishops more scope.} Bg6 {The importance of having c4 already played is seen in the line ( 7...Be4 8.Nc3 when the second knight harasses the bishop and ensures it doesn't stay alive.} 8. Nxg6 {The simplest is to eliminate the bishop immediately, not having to worry when to do so.} hxg6 {The opening of the h-file leaves the pawn on h2 under the attack of the bishop and the rook, but the next simple move solves the problem.} 9. g3 $1 ({This structure is very strong because by placing the pawns on the same colour as the opponent's bishop, White successfully limits the activity of the said bishop. This is why} 9. g3 {is better than}) (9. h3 {in this case.}) 9... Nbd7 {Black develops along the usual Slav lines.} 10. Nd2 {White should be patient in this position. They have the long-term advantage of the two bishops, but first they should finish development. The knight on d2 defends the pawn on c4 and also controls the e4-square (thus preventing a possible jump by Black with ...Ne4). White will continue with Bf3, Qc2 and Rd1, concentrating the forces in the centre, with the ultimate aim to push e4 and open the position. Depending on the circumstances, this can be preceded by the development of the other bishop to b2 after playing b3 first.} *

