1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} c6 {This move is characteristic of the Slav Defence.} 4. Be2 {White continues as usual. Now Black has three types of development:  * 1. To develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4 before playing ...e6;  * 2. To play ...e6 immediately; or  * 3. To play the fianchetto with ...g6 and ...Bg7.} Bg4 {Black develops the bishop before playing ...e6.} 5. h3 {White follows the rule of thumb to insert this useful move, which forces Black to determine the position of the bishop.} Bh5 {Black keeps the bishop alive.} ({In case of} 5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8. b3 O-O 9. c4 Nbd7 10. Nc3 {White's development is identical as in the other lines, with the plan again being to execute the e4 push after Bb2, Qc2, Rad1 and Rfe1.}) 6. O-O {White completes the usual development.} e6 7. c4 {The bishop on h5 cannot be trapped by the knights, a plan that worked well for White in the line with 4...Bf5, so in this variation, White employs the plan of a queenside expansion with c5 and b4. That is the reason why c4 is played immediately, so that the b-pawn can come to b4 in one move.} Bd6 ({Black follows the standard Slav development. It's worth noting that if Black doesn't develop the bishop to this square and prefers} 7... Be7 {, then there is little point in pushing c5 as the pawn doesn't attack the bishop in that case. Therefore White continues with the standard plan of} 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. b3 {followed by Bb2 when the idea is to plant a knight on e5 with Ne5 and possibly support it by f4.}) 8. Nc3 {White first develops the knight before expanding.} O-O ({Black can also start with} 8... Nbd7 {, but that won't change White's plans after} 9. c5 {followed by b4 etc.}) 9. c5 {This is White's simplest plan. White gains space on the queenside and simply advances with the pawns on that side of the board.} Bc7 {The bishop stays on the h2-b8 diagonal, as one of Black's main ideas is to execute the ...e5-advance.} 10. b4 {The idea is to continue with b5.} Nbd7 {Black wants to implement the plan of pushing ...e5.} ({The move} 10... a6 {is met by} 11. a4 {followed by Bb2 (to defend the rook on a1 in case of an opening of the a-file) and b5.}) 11. b5 {White is the first to establish contact on the queenside. Next the rook will come to the b-file with Rb1 and White will decide when it would be the best moment to open it by taking on c6.} Z0 ({If now Black pushes in the centre with} 11... e5 {then after the exchanges} 12. Nxe5 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Rb1 {White also obtains the beautiful d4-square for the knight, from where it targets the weak pawn on c6.}) *

