1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} e6 {Black can continue with the symmetry and often will. The development of the bishop to f5 or g4 is possible, but these moves will transpose to the lines analysed after 3...c6, for example:} (3... Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. h3 {( always play this little move when Black lands a bishop on g4 )} Bh5 {or 5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 Bd6 7.O-O O-O 8.c4 c6} 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 {and we have arrived in the so-called Slav structures.}) ({Similar is} 3... Bf5 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 {. In case Black opts to push the pawn to c5 instead of c6, then we analyse these positions after the move}) (3... c5 {.}) 4. Be2 {White develops the kingside.} Bd6 {This move develops the bishop to a more active square.} 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {White employs the known plan of development, the bishop comes to b2 before pushing c4.} b6 {Black can continue with the symmetrical development.} 7. Bb2 {White develops the bishop and will continue with c4 next.} Bb7 8. c4 {White advances in the centre and now can decide where to place the knight. Usually the more active square c3 is preferred.} c5 ({Again the symmetrical approach. If Black captures the pawn then White recaptures with the pawn and obtains a compact pawn mass after} 8... dxc4 9. bxc4 {when the plan is to develop with Nc3 and aim for a further advance in the centre with d5.}) ({The move} 8... Nbd7 {transposes to the lines analysed [/variation/44724152/#/9/w] after StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/3bpn2/3p4/3P4/1P2PN2/P1P1BPPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 0 6EndFEN 6...Nbd7 7.Bb2 b6 8.c4 Bb7 .}) 9. cxd5 {Taking the pawn on d5 is the common reaction for White when the four pawns are symmetrically placed in the centre. The idea is two-fold: if Black recaptures with a piece, White would like to advance in the centre by e4; if Black recaptures with a pawn, then that pawn limits the activity of the bishop on b7 with White having solid control of the blockading square in front of it.} exd5 {With this recapture Black maintains a pawn presence in the centre.} ({In case of} 9... Bxd5 $6 10. Nc3 {White threatens to capture the bishop on d5 and if the bishop retreats then} Bb7 11. Nb5 {targets the other bishop, with the cute trap after} Be7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Nc7 {winning the rook on a8.}) ({The capture with a knight} 9... Nxd5 {is met by} 10. Nbd2 {or 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.Nbd2 when the same position is reached via the move order [/variation/44724155/#/11/w] StartFENrnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/3P4/4PN2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R_w_KQkq_-_2_5EndFEN 4...Be7 5.O-O O-O 6.b3 b6 7.Bb2 Bb7 8.c4 c5 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.Nbd2 avoiding the exchange of knights that would have occurred in case the knight was developed on c3 and planning Nc4 to target the bishop on d6.}) 10. Nc3 {The knight is developed on a square from where it targets the pawn on d5, but can also harass the bishop on d6 with Nb5. White has harmoniously completed development. White's plan is to place the rooks on c1 and e1 and then drop the bishop to f1, play g3 in order to transfer the bishop to g2, placing it on the long diagonal, with the idea to target the pawn on d5.} *

