1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} e6 {Black can continue with the symmetry and often will. The development of the bishop to f5 or g4 is possible, but these moves will transpose to the lines analysed after 3...c6, for example:} (3... Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. h3 {( always play this little move when Black lands a bishop on g4 )} Bh5 {or 5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 Bd6 7.O-O O-O 8.c4 c6} 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 {and we have arrived in the so-called Slav structures.}) ({Similar is} 3... Bf5 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 {. In case Black opts to push the pawn to c5 instead of c6, then we analyse these positions after the move}) (3... c5 {.}) 4. Be2 {White develops the kingside.} Bd6 {This move develops the bishop to a more active square.} 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {White employs the known plan of development, the bishop comes to b2 before pushing c4.} Nbd7 ({The move} 6... c5 {after} 7. dxc5 {( forcing the bishop to move again! )} Bxc5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. a3 {leads to the position after the move order 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3 Be7 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.Bb2 O-O 9.a3 [/variation/44724142/#/9/w].}) 7. Bb2 {White is now ready to play in the centre with c4.} b6 {Black decides to finish development with ...Bb7 before playing in the centre.} 8. c4 {White continues with c4 so that it's possible to follow up with Nc3.} Bb7 9. Nc3 {The c3-square is a more active one for the knight than the d2-square. From c3 the knight controls the b5, d5 and e4-squares.} c5 {Black strikes back in the centre. When these four pawns (c4, d4, c5, d5) are facing each other, the rule of thumb for White is to take on d5.} ({Other moves are} 9... a6 {( preventing a possible Nb5 )} 10. a4 {with the idea of a5, to harass Black's queenside,}) ({or} 9... Ne4 10. Rc1 {and now the most commonly-played move} f5 $6 {is met by} 11. Nb5 {when the bishop cannot move because} Be7 $2 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxc7 {wins material for White as the rook on a8 is hanging and if it moves then Ne6 attacks both the queen on d8 and the rook on f8.}) 10. cxd5 {Now we have two scenarios: if Black recaptures with a piece, White's plan is to advance in the centre by e4, while if Black recaptures with a pawn, then that pawn on d5 gets in the way of the the bishop on b7 with White having eternal control of the blockading square d4 in front of it.} Nxd5 ({In case of} 10... exd5 11. Rc1 {White will place the other rook on e1 and will transfer the bishop to f1, play g3 and continue the bishop journey with Bg2, from where it guards the kingside and looks toward the pawn on d5.}) 11. Nxd5 {White captures the centralised knight.} Bxd5 ({In case of} 11... exd5 12. Rc1 {the plan of Re1, Bf1, g3 and Bg2 remains the same.}) 12. Qd3 {The plan is to advance with e4-e5.} Z0 ({Black cannot stop it with} 12... Nf6 {because after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 $1 {White threatens both e4 and Bxf6 followed by Qxh7 mate.}) *

