1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} e6 {Black can continue with the symmetry and often will. The development of the bishop to f5 or g4 is possible, but these moves will transpose to the lines analysed after 3...c6, for example:} (3... Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. h3 {( always play this little move when Black lands a bishop on g4 )} Bh5 {or 5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 Bd6 7.O-O O-O 8.c4 c6} 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 {and we have arrived in the so-called Slav structures.}) ({Similar is} 3... Bf5 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 {. In case Black opts to push the pawn to c5 instead of c6, then we analyse these positions after the move}) (3... c5 {.}) 4. Be2 {White develops the kingside.} Bd6 {This move develops the bishop to a more active square.} 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {White employs the known plan of development, the bishop comes to b2 before pushing c4.} Nbd7 ({The move} 6... c5 {after} 7. dxc5 {( forcing the bishop to move again! )} Bxc5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. a3 {leads to the position after the move order 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3 Be7 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.Bb2 O-O 9.a3 [/variation/44724142/#/9/w].}) 7. Bb2 {White is now ready to play in the centre with c4.} c5 8. dxc5 {White follows the rule of thumb that once Black's dark-squared bishop has moved, this time to d6, White should capture the pawn on c5 in order to force it to waste a move to recapture. Here Black has the additional option to capture with the knight, but White still has good play in that case, too.} Nxc5 ({This recapture is better than wasting a move with the bishop with} 8... Bxc5 9. a3 {when White wants to expand on the queenside with b4, c4 etc. and if} a5 {then} 10. c4 {with Nc3 to come, targeting the weakened square on b5.}) 9. Nbd2 {White completes development and takes control of the e4-square, so it's possible to capture a black knight should it appear there. Otherwise, White plans the usual c4-advance.} b6 {Black wants to develop the bishop.} ({In case of a knight jump} 9... Nce4 $6 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. c4 {White continues with the planned central advance, attacking Black's pawn on d5.}) 10. c4 {The ensuing play will happen in the centre. White will place the queen's rook on c1 and his ideas include moves like cxd5 (in order to free the c4-square for the knight from d2), followed by Nc4 (attacking the bishop on d6), the b4-advance, to chase away the knight on c5, placing the knight from f3 in the centre on d4, or sometimes even the queen (after the knight from d2 moves to c4) can come to the central square on d4.} *

