{Now a sample line is 12...Rc8 13.Ba6 Rc7 14.Qe2 , with the queen supporting the central advance e4 from the e2-square, while at the same time liberating the d1-square for the rook from f1.} 1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} e6 {Black can continue with the symmetry and often will. The development of the bishop to f5 or g4 is possible, but these moves will transpose to the lines analysed after 3...c6, for example:} (3... Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. h3 {( always play this little move when Black lands a bishop on g4 )} Bh5 {or 5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 Bd6 7.O-O O-O 8.c4 c6} 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 {and we have arrived in the so-called Slav structures.}) ({Similar is} 3... Bf5 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 {. In case Black opts to push the pawn to c5 instead of c6, then we analyse these positions after the move}) (3... c5 {.}) 4. Be2 {White develops the kingside.} Be7 ({The symmetrical reply. The move} 4... c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. b3 {is analysed after 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3. [/variation/44724142/#/6/w]}) 5. O-O {White first finishes the development of the kingside before turning their attention to the queenside.} O-O 6. b3 {White develops following their plan.} b6 ({Black continues with the symmetry. In case of} 6... c5 7. dxc5 $1 {( the rule of thumb, take on c5 when Black has already moved the dark-squared bishop to force it to move again and lose time )} Bxc5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. a3 {we have a transposition to the position analysed via the move order 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3 Be7 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.Bb2 O-O 9.a3 [/variation/44724142/#/9/w].}) 7. Bb2 {Both sides develop their pieces, with Black copying White.} Bb7 8. c4 {White achieves the central advance.} Nbd7 {This move is a preparation for the pushing of the c-pawn with ...c5.} 9. Nc3 {White develops the knight on the more active square on c3 (compared to d2).} c5 10. cxd5 {With the four pawns in the centre White follows the rule of thumb to capture on d5. In such situations, we have the two scenarios we have already described in some of the other lines: if Black recaptures with a piece, White's plan is to advance in the centre by advancing the e-pawn, while if Black recaptures with a pawn, then White has eternal control of the blockading square d4 in front of the d5-pawn, which limits the mobility of the bishop on b7.} Nxd5 ({It's better to recapture with a piece. After} 10... exd5 11. Rc1 {White's plan is the relocation of the light-squared bishop to g2 after Re1, Bf1, g3 and Bg2, to strengthen the kingside and target the pawn on d5.}) 11. Nxd5 {White gives Black a second chance to take with a pawn, which Black should decline.} Bxd5 ({After} 11... exd5 12. Rc1 {White's plan remains the same as in the previous comment: Re1, Bf1, g3 and Bg2.}) 12. Rc1 {The position is almost identical to the one arising via the move order [/variation/44724152/#/11/b] StartFENrnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/3P4/4PN2/PPP1BPPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4EndFEN 4...Bd6 5.O-O O-O 6.b3 Nbd7 7.Bb2 b6 8.c4 Bb7 9.Nc3 c5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 , the only difference being the placement of the black dark-squared bishop - here it is on e7 while in the variation above it is on d6. This difference affects White's choice - the bishop's position on d6 made it more vulnerable, so White's proposed move was 12.Qd3 , intending e4-e5, hitting both bishops along the way. Here, however, the bishop is safer on e7, so the move Qd3 would make less impact. Therefore White completes development by activating the rook first and awaiting developments.} Z0 *

