1. d4 d5 {The symmetrical reply is one of the most common replies. Black places a pawn in the centre just like White.} 2. Nf3 {White starts the development of the kingside by first developing the knight, at the same time increasing control of the e5-square. The intended continuation, as explained in the Introduction, is to play e3, Be2 and O-O.} Nf6 {This is Black's most common set-up, even though often Black develops the knight at a later stage.} 3. e3 {White continues with the development of the kingside, preparing Be2 and short castle.} e6 {Black can continue with the symmetry and often will. The development of the bishop to f5 or g4 is possible, but these moves will transpose to the lines analysed after 3...c6, for example:} (3... Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. h3 {( always play this little move when Black lands a bishop on g4 )} Bh5 {or 5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 Bd6 7.O-O O-O 8.c4 c6} 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 {and we have arrived in the so-called Slav structures.}) ({Similar is} 3... Bf5 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 c6 {. In case Black opts to push the pawn to c5 instead of c6, then we analyse these positions after the move}) (3... c5 {.}) 4. Be2 {White develops the kingside.} Be7 ({The symmetrical reply. The move} 4... c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. b3 {is analysed after 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3. [/variation/44724142/#/6/w]}) 5. O-O {White first finishes the development of the kingside before turning their attention to the queenside.} O-O 6. b3 {White develops following their plan.} b6 ({Black continues with the symmetry. In case of} 6... c5 7. dxc5 $1 {( the rule of thumb, take on c5 when Black has already moved the dark-squared bishop to force it to move again and lose time )} Bxc5 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. a3 {we have a transposition to the position analysed via the move order 3...c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O e6 6.b3 Be7 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.Bb2 O-O 9.a3 [/variation/44724142/#/9/w].}) 7. Bb2 {Both sides develop their pieces, with Black copying White.} Bb7 8. c4 {White achieves the central advance.} c5 {Still symmetrical, but Black can deviate, of course. In case of the capture of the pawn on c4 with ( 8...dxc4 White recapture with the pawn to establish a pawn preponderance in the centre with 9.bxc4 when the plan is to develop with Nc3 and later aim for the advance of the d-pawn with d5.} 9. cxd5 {The rule of thumb applies here as well - with the four pawns facing each other on the central squares c4, d4, c5 and d5, White captures the pawn on d5.} Nxd5 {This is the better recapture. In case of a capture with a pawn, White develops along the already mentioned lines: Nc3, Rc1, Re1, Bf1, g3 and Bg2, to secure the kingside and put pressure on the pawn on d5.} 10. dxc5 ({Resolving the tension between the central pawns makes the position easier to play. This capture also opens the long diagonal for the bishop on b2. It's also possible to start with} 10. Nbd2 {and then capture on c5.}) 10... Bxc5 ({Naturally, Black won't be saddling themselves with an isolated pawn after} 10... bxc5 $2 {when the pawn on c5 is weak and can be attacked after} 11. Nbd2 {followed Qc2 and using the rooks on the c-file.}) 11. Nbd2 ({White completes development. While there is nothing wrong with} 11. Nc3 {, developing the knight to d2 bears more resemblance with some of the other lines in this chapter. The plan is to expand on the queenside with a3 and b4 and the knight from d2 can go to c4 or e4, while the queen can come to b3, to free the first rank for the rooks, which will be placed on c1 and d1. Note that the tempting sacrifice on e3 backfires for Black because after} Bxe3 $2 12. fxe3 Nxe3 13. Qe1 Nxf1 14. Bxf1 {White's two pieces are worth more than Black's rook and two pawns because Black's rooks cannot easily be activated, while White's light pieces, both knights and bishops, are already fully engaged in play, and White can use them to start activities against Black's king with ideas like Ne4, Qg3 and so on. For a good illustration of how to play in these positions take a look at the model game Dominguez-Tomaszewski [/variation/44740509] .}) *

