1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 {In the theoretical part the recommendation is to place the bishop on e2, but soon we will achieve the type of position we will often reach from the course, with the bishop's placement of little value.} c5 5. b3 Nc6 6. O-O Be7 {With the bishop on d3 Black could have forced White to close the long diagonal with a pawn on ( d4 after 6...cxd4 7.Nxd4 Nxd4 and now the bishop on d3 blocks the queen's path to the d4-square, which means that White must play 8.exd4 , something we wanted to avoid in the course.} 7. dxc5 $1 {Dominguez follows the rule of thumb to capture on c5 only when Black has already moved the bishop from f8, thus forcing it to lose time to recapture the pawn.} Bxc5 8. Bb2 {Now the bishop enjoys an open long diagonal.} b6 9. a3 {Another idea from the course - White expands on the queenside with b4 before executing the c4-push.} Bb7 ({In case of} 9... a5 {, which weakens the b5-square, White would have taken advantage of that weakness by sending the knight there after} 10. c4 {and Nc3.}) 10. Nbd2 {A bit imprecise, because now the knight loses the option to be developed to c3 in case Black plays ...a5. It was better to start with b4 and then Nbd2.} O-O ({An imprecision by Black in return. He could have taken advantage of White's last move with the move} 10... a5 {, stopping White's expansion with b4.}) 11. b4 {Now White corrects his mistake.} Be7 12. c4 {This is White's standard play in these positions. Now after the pawns are exchanged} dxc4 13. Nxc4 {White has good central control, with the plan being to move the queen from the initial square, connect the rooks and place them on the open c and d-files.} h6 {A useful move to open an escape square for the king on h7, but this doesn't solve Black's main problem, which is the position of the queen on the open central files and the lack of a safe square for it.} 14. Qe2 {White immediately tries to take advantage of the queen's exposed position, as now the threat is Rfd1 and Bh7.} Rc8 15. Rac1 {It was possible to play Rfd1, threatening Bh7, but White decides to improve the position of the other rook first.} Qd5 {Black desperately seeks to find a safe refuge for the queen. The idea is to send it to h5.} 16. e4 {White uses the fact that he can take advantage of the queen's exposed position to advance in the centre - this is another motif for White in these positions.} Qh5 17. e5 {White gained space by advancing the e-pawn. Now the knight from f6 needs to move, which opens up attacking possibilities against the black king.} Nd5 18. Qe4 {This is the main idea when White plays e5 to chase away the knight from f6: the knight no longer controls the e4 and h7-squares: the e4-square is used by the white queen and together with the bishop on d3 they create a mating threat on the h7-square.} Qg6 ({In case of} 18... g6 19. Nd6 $1 {White uses another advantage of having a pawn on e5: control of the d6-square, so the knight lands there with devastating effect. After} Bxd6 20. exd6 {the long diagonal is opened for the bishop on b2 and White can use it to create mating threats along it with the help of b5, to remove the knight from c6 in order to obtain access to the d4-square, and then Qd4.}) 19. g3 $6 ({In a blitz game White plays a lazy move when he could have been more forceful. After} 19. Qxg6 fxg6 {he shouldn't become greedy with} 20. Bxg6 $2 Nf4 {, as now the bishop on g6 is attacked and there is the threat of ...Ne2, but he should simply play 20.Rfe1 and his superior pawn structure, together with the threat of Nd6 give him a solid advantage.}) 19... Nf4 {Now Black exchanges queens without the worsening of his kingside structure.} 20. Qxg6 Nxg6 21. Be4 {White places the light-squared bishop on the central e4-square, thus neutralising the bishop on b7.} Nd8 {A passive move that seeks exchanges, but at the cost of worsening of Black's position. Placing the rook from f8 on the same square would have been preferable.} 22. Nfd2 {White wants to recapture on e4 with the knight, when he would have absolute control of the d6-square.} Bd5 {Black insists on the exchange of the light-squared bishops, but this worsens his structure because, after the ensuing exchange, the pawn on d5 can easily be attacked.} 23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Ne3 {Black cannot defend the pawn on d5. He tries to counterattack, but White is careful.} Rxc1 25. Rxc1 f6 26. Nxd5 {White won a pawn and also threatens to invade on the c-file with Rc7, placing the rook on the seventh rank.} fxe5 27. Nxe7+ Nxe7 28. Rc7 {It was also possible to simply capture the pawn on e5. Instead, White maximises the activity of the rook as the pawn won't run away.} Nec6 {Trying to defend everything, but this is short-lived.} 29. Nc4 ({A good alternative was} 29. b5 {and the knight must leave the c6-square from where it defended both pawns on a7 and e5.}) 29... Rf7 30. Rc8 {This pins the knight on d8 and introduces the threats of Nxe5 and b5.} Rf8 31. b5 {Finally kicking away the knight on c6.} Nd4 32. a4 {Simply defending the pawn on a4. Black's position will soon collapse against the attack of the better-coordinated white pieces.} Nf3+ 33. Kh1 {Avoiding checks from e1 in case of Kg2, though that was also possible.} Nf7 34. Rc7 {The pawn on a7 cannot be protected.} N7g5 {Black wants to create threats against the white king, but after White's next move, everything is under control.} 35. Nxe5 {White picks up the pawn and opens the long diagonal for the bishop, thus targeting the pawn on g7.} Nxe5 36. Bxe5 {The pawn on g7 is under attack.} Rf7 37. Rxf7 Kxf7 38. Bb8 {The game is over as Black the pawns on the queenside are both lost.} Ne4 39. Bxa7 Nc5 40. a5 {A nice concluding move, taking advantage of the pin on the pawn on b6. White's pawns will soon promote, and Black resigned.} 1-0

