1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. b3 O-O 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Bb2 {Via the starting move order of the Slav Defence, we landed in the position explored in the theoretical chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1].} Rc8 {Black prepares a possible advance with ...c5.} 11. e4 {White executes the main idea. It's also possible to prepare this advance by placing the rooks on the d and e-files.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 {Black chases away the white queen from the central position.} 14. Qc2 {An alternative is to place the queen on the h4-square.} Qe7 {Black's main idea in the position is to advance with ...c5, to open the long diagonal for the bishop on b7. In such a scenario, White should decide between two ideas:  * to capture on c5 and obtain a pawn majority on the queenside (his 3 pawns against Black's 2 pawns); or  * to advance in the centre with d5 and obtain a passed pawn on the d-file.} ({From Black's perspective, it was better to do so immediately, after} 14... c5 15. Rad1 cxd4 16. Nxd4 {White obtains 3 pawns versus Black's 2 on the queenside and the plan will be to fight for control over the d-file in combination with the preparation for an advance of those 3 pawns.}) 15. Rad1 $1 {White activates the rook and also prepares against a possible ...c5 by supporting the advance of the d-pawn.} Rfd8 ({White is ready for} 15... c5 $6 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. cxd5 Nxd5 {( 11...Bxd5? 12.Bxf6 Qxf6 13.Rxd5 wins a piece )} 18. Bc4 Nf6 19. Rfe1 {and White obtains a decisive attack as Black cannot hide all his pieces.}) 16. Rfe1 {A standard move, placing the rook on the same file as the opponent's queen.} c5 {Black wants to activate the bishop on b7, but this backfires thanks to White's preparation to meet this advance.} 17. d5 $1 {The strong reply.} exd5 18. Bd3 {White's pieces are perfectly poised for an attack on the kingside.} Qf8 19. Bxf6 {White regains the pawn with check now.} gxf6 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. cxd5 {White won a pawn, and in addition to the material advantage, he also has an attack against Black's weakened king.} Re8 22. Qf5 {The queen wants to come to the h-file to create threats against the black king.} Qh6 {Black rushes to control the h-file, but he leaves the other flank undefended.} 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Qd7 {A triple attack!} Qf8 25. Qh3 ({It was also possible to win another pawn with} 25. Qxb7 Kxh7 26. Qxa7 {, but White returns to the idea of placing a queen on the h-file.}) 25... Bf4 26. Bb1+ Bh6 27. Qf5 {Threatening mate on h7.} Qg7 28. d6 {Black is tied down to the defence against mate on h7, so White uses the second trump, the passed pawn on the d-file.} Rg8 29. g3 {Of course, White won't blunder mate on g2.} Rd8 30. d7 {The pawn is safely protected and it completely ties down Black's pieces.} b5 31. Nh4 {White removes the knight from the attacked square on f3.} Bg5 {Black attacks the knight on h4.} 32. Qg4 {White simply defends it and plans to transfer it to the dominant f5-square.} Bc6 33. Nf5 Qh7 34. Ne7 {The final double attack - both the queen on h7 and the bishop on c6 are attacked. White wins more material now.} Bxd7 35. Bxh7 Bxg4 36. Rxd8+ Kxh7 37. f4 {White has a rook for a bishop but will soon win more material.} Bh6 38. Nd5 c4 39. Nxf6+ 1-0

