1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} d6 {A flexible move that allows for the development of the bishop to f5 or g4. Another idea behind this move is to play ...Nbd7 to support the ...e5-advance.} 3. e3 {White continues with the usual plan.} Nbd7 {The development of the knight on d7 is the alternative plan. Black wants to push the e-pawn forward.} 4. Be2 {White continues with the development of the kingside and prepares a short castle.} e5 {Black executes the central advance and intends to follow up with ...Be7 and a short castle.} ({If Black switches to the fianchetto with} 4... g6 {then after the standard developing moves} 5. O-O Bg7 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 {we have a transposition to the line analysed [/variation/44740764/#/7/w] after StartFENrnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2EndFEN 2...g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Be2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.b3 Nbd7 7.Bb2}) 5. O-O {White finishes the development of the kingside.} Be7 ({Black plans to castle short. If they advance with the central pawn further with} 5... e4 {then after} 6. Nfd2 d5 7. c4 c6 8. Nc3 {followed by f3 White is attacking Black's advanced central pawns from both sides - the pawn on c4 and the knight on c3 are attacking the pawn on d5, while both knights and the pawn on f3 are attacking the pawn on e4.}) 6. c4 {White expands and plans to develop the knight on the c3-square.} O-O {Black has completed the development of the kingside.} 7. Nc3 {White now develops the queenside. The plan is to start with Qc2 to control the central e4-square and ensure against a possible advance of the black e-pawn, and then follow up with the usual development of the dark-squared bishop with b3 and Bb2.} c6 {A preparatory move for the central advance ...e4 because the immediate ( 7...e4? is bad because after 8.Nd2 both White's knights are attacking the pawn on e4 and Black can only defend it once, meaning White will win that pawn.} 8. Qc2 $1 {An important move, preventing the advance ...e4. Next White will continue with the development of the queenside with b3 and Bb2 and obtain harmonious development. After that they will consider expansion in the centre with e4 or on the queenside with a3, b4.} *

