1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} d6 {A flexible move that allows for the development of the bishop to f5 or g4. Another idea behind this move is to play ...Nbd7 to support the ...e5-advance.} 3. e3 {White continues with the usual plan.} Bg4 ({Note that the move} 3... g6 {after} 4. Be2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {would transpose to the lines after 2...g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Be2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.b3.}) 4. h3 {The rule of thumb in action - White harasses the bishop once it lands on g4.} Bh5 {In case Black captures on f3 then after ( 4...Bxf3 5.Qxf3 the pawn on b7 is attacked by the queen. When Black defends it, White will continue with c4, Nc3, Bd3 (this time the bishop can be deployed on d3 and leave the e2-square available for the queen to retreat from f3) with good control of the centre, space advantage and the two bishops.} 5. Be2 {White breaks the pin on the knight on the d1-h5 diagonal and continues with the usual development. Now Black has several options, but White's development will remain the same - castle and then advance in the centre with the c-pawn with c4 and follow up with Nc3.} Nbd7 {This move is more in line with Black's set-up. The knight is safe on d7 and supports a possible advance with the e-pawn with ...e5.} 6. O-O {White continues with the development.} e5 {Black advances in the centre and wants to develop with ...Be7 and ...O-O.} ({In case of a more passive set-up with} 6... e6 {White continues with} 7. c4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {and now with Black being passive in the centre nothing stops White from expanding in the centre and taking full control of it with} 9. e4 {when the dark-squared bishop will be developed on e3.}) 7. c4 {White continues with the intended plan. Next the knight will be developed to c3.} Be7 ({Black wants to castle. In case of an advance with} 7... e4 8. Nfd2 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 {White will continue with the planned move Nc3 to attack the pawn on e4 and then if necessary with f3, to force Black to capture on f3 and open the f-file for the white pieces.}) 8. Nc3 O-O 9. b4 {White employs a more ambitious version of the usual idea of b3 and Bb2. The reason is that Black's queenside is almost deserted and Black is not preventing White in any way from expanding on that side of the board. The plan is simple, to push the queenside pawns as far as possible with a4, b5, a5, to develop the bishop to a3 and then according to circumstances to develop the queen and rooks so as to support a further advance of the queenside pawns.} *

