1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} d6 {A flexible move that allows for the development of the bishop to f5 or g4. Another idea behind this move is to play ...Nbd7 to support the ...e5-advance.} 3. e3 {White continues with the usual plan.} Bg4 ({Note that the move} 3... g6 {after} 4. Be2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {would transpose to the lines after 2...g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Be2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.b3.}) 4. h3 {The rule of thumb in action - White harasses the bishop once it lands on g4.} Bh5 {In case Black captures on f3 then after ( 4...Bxf3 5.Qxf3 the pawn on b7 is attacked by the queen. When Black defends it, White will continue with c4, Nc3, Bd3 (this time the bishop can be deployed on d3 and leave the e2-square available for the queen to retreat from f3) with good control of the centre, space advantage and the two bishops.} 5. Be2 {White breaks the pin on the knight on the d1-h5 diagonal and continues with the usual development. Now Black has several options, but White's development will remain the same - castle and then advance in the centre with the c-pawn with c4 and follow up with Nc3.} Nc6 $6 {The most commonly-played move, but one that is a bit out of place in Black's set-up because the knight can be attacked by White's advancing d-pawn with d5.} 6. O-O {White completes the development of the kingside and will continue with c4 and Nc3, like in the majority of the lines.} e5 ({Alternatively Black can play} 6... e6 {, though after the standard developing moves} 7. c4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {and White's very strong advance with} 9. d5 $1 {, we see the drawbacks of the development of the knight to c6. After} exd5 10. cxd5 {Black is under severe pressure, especially as the most natural move} Ne5 $2 {leads to a loss of a pawn after} 11. Nxe5 {( the bishop on h5 is attacked, so Black's next move is forced )} Bxe2 12. Nxf7 $1 {( an important tactic, White captures a pawn and attacks the black queen )} Bxd1 13. Nxd8 Bc2 14. Ne6 {and the knight escaped while winning a pawn along the way, in addition to landing on the fantastic outpost on e6.}) 7. c4 {White develops along the standard lines, intending Nc3.} Be7 {Black intends to castle and this is the best option, because reacting in the centre gives White a solid advantage.} ({For example} 7... exd4 8. exd4 {opens up the c1-h6 diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and White will continue with Nc3 and d5, harassing the knight on c6.}) ({Also,} 7... e4 $6 8. Nfd2 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 {exposes the pawn on e4 to attacks after Nc3 and the curious maneuver Qd1-c2, in addition to the undermining move f3.}) 8. Nc3 {White develops the knight on c3, from where it controls the central squares d5 and e4. The latter is especially important in case Black decides to advance with the e-pawn further.} O-O {Black completes development. Again reacting in the centre is inferior, for the same reasons as in the previous comment.} ({For example} 8... exd4 9. exd4 {with d5 to come next,}) ({or} 8... e4 $6 9. Nd2 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 {and Black loses the pawn on e4 as it cannot be defended.}) 9. d5 ({An ambitious plan. It's perfectly possible to continue along the usual lines with} 9. b3 {, the standard development that prepares the deployment of the bishop to b2. The move 9.b3 contains the psychological trap of luring Black to react in the centre in one of the two ways already shown in the previous comments, to take on d4 or advance with ...e4, both of which are not Black's best options. Nevertheless, the advance in the centre is a very good plan the student should be aware of, as by advancing in the centre White takes advantage of the more exposed position of the knight on c6 and starts an attack on the kingside.}) 9... Nb8 10. g4 $1 {The important follow-up. White forces the bishop to retreat and will continue with a pawn advance.} Bg6 {The 'sacrifice' on g4 is completely fruitless as ( 10...Nxg4? 11.hxg4 Bxg4 12.Kh1 followed by Nh2 and Rg1 squashes any hopes of an attack that Black may have had.} 11. Nh4 {With this move White frees the path for the f-pawn to advance ahead. The threat is f4-f5 to trap the bishop on g6. If the bishop cannot be trapped the knight on h4 can either be exchanged for it, giving White the two bishops, or the knight can drop back to g2 to support the advance of the f-pawn. In either case, White has a strong attack against Black's kingside.} *

