1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} e6 {Black stays flexible in the centre by not playing ...d5. Here we will examine the lines where Black avoids this move initially, since playing it will inevitably lead to a transposition to the positions we explored in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1].} 3. e3 {Black's development doesn't affect White's, who continues with the standard set-up of Be2 and O-O.} b6 {The development of the bishop to b7 is an alternative, leading to the so-called Queen's Indian setup.} 4. Be2 {White plays the intended moves.} Bb7 5. O-O {White develops the kingside first.} Be7 {Black intends to castle and then play in the centre either by pushing the c-pawn with ...c5 or the d-pawn with ...d5. White's next two moves are based on the general plan, but at the same time they are intended at preventing Black's play with ...c5.} 6. c4 {This is part of White's plan and here the reason for playing c4 and Nc3 before b3 and Bb2 is the control of the d5-square. This will become obvious on the next move.} O-O {Black completes development by castling short.} 7. Nc3 {White controls the d5-square and now is ready to deal with Black's advance with ...c5 by pushing the d-pawn forward.} d5 ({As explained,} 7... c5 $6 8. d5 $1 {gives White a space advantage and locks in the bishop on b7, when White will next continue with e4 to solidify the centre.}) ({Similar is} 7... d6 $6 8. d5 $1 {followed by e4 when White obtains a big central space advantage. Therefore, Black should push their d-pawn forward to stop White from doing the same.}) ({Black can seek exchanges with} 7... Ne4 {, but after} 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. b3 {White continues with the development of the bishop to b2 and then seeks to play Nd2 and e4 to expand in the centre.}) 8. b3 {Since White's pawn advance with the d-pawn has been stopped, White reverts to the usual development of the dark-squared bishop to b2.} c5 ({Black advances in the centre. In case of} 8... Nbd7 9. Bb2 {we have a transposition to the position we analyse in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/variation/44724154/#/9/w] via the move-order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Be2 Be7 5.O-O O-O 6.b3 b6 7.Bb2 Bb7 8.c4 Nbd7 . Now we have the typical pawn structure in the centre when the four pawns c4, d4, c5 and d5 are facing each other and the usual rule of thumb in such situations is to capture on d5. Note the difference with the almost identical line from the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 - here White has a knight developed on c3, while in that chapter they had a bishop developed on b2. Another alternative is to capture on c4, after}) (8... dxc4 {White recaptures toward the centre with a pawn} 9. bxc4 {and after} c5 10. Bb2 cxd4 11. exd4 Nc6 12. Rc1 {White's plan is to execute the central d5-advance.}) 9. cxd5 {White follows the rule of thumb.} Nxd5 {Here the difference from the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 is obvious - the knight on c3 is attacked, while there with a bishop on b2 instead of a knight on c3 White could capture the pawn on c5.} ({In the case of a capture with a pawn, White continues with} 9... exd5 10. Bb2 {and then the plan already known from the chapter Black Plays 1...d5: Rc1, Re1, Bf1, g3 and Bg2, solidifying the kingside and taking aim at the pawn on d5.}) 10. Nxd5 {It's simplest to eliminate the attack on the knight on c3 by exchanging it.} Bxd5 ({Black can also recapture with the queen, but after} 10... Qxd5 11. Ba3 $5 {White introduces an unpleasant pin on the a3-f8 diagonal, thanks to the fact that the queen is no longer on its starting position from where it defended the bishop on e7. With the bishop on e7 undefended, Black cannot capture the pawn on d4 as that would lead to a loss of piece after} cxd4 $4 12. Bxe7 {. Otherwise, White will continue by placing the rook on the c-file or taking the pawn on c5 with the d4-pawn.}) 11. dxc5 {White clarifies the position in the centre by exchanging the pawns. This opens the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop, which will come to b2 on the next move.} Bxc5 12. Bb2 {White finished development and the subsequent play is fairly simple. White wants to expand on the queenside with moves like a3 and b4. Once the black bishop is no longer on c5, then White can play Qd4, threatening mate on g7. The rooks will come to c1 and d1, for control of the central files. One trick in the position is to play b4 without the help of a3, for example after} Z0 (12... Nd7 13. b4 Bxb4 $4 14. Qd4 {, White threatens both mate on g7 and attacks the bishop on b4, thus winning a piece.}) *

