1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} e6 {Black stays flexible in the centre by not playing ...d5. Here we will examine the lines where Black avoids this move initially, since playing it will inevitably lead to a transposition to the positions we explored in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1].} 3. e3 {Black's development doesn't affect White's, who continues with the standard set-up of Be2 and O-O.} c5 ({Apart from} 3... b6 {, the other moves are not very critical (or very good. )}) ({For example} 3... Be7 {doesn't alter White's plans as they continue with} 4. Be2 {and O-O, when play will likely transpose to the other lines after Black plays ...d5 or ...c5 in the centre.}) ({Giving a check with} 3... Bb4+ $6 {only forces White to play a move that is part of the plan with} 4. Nbd2 {when White can later use the exposed position of the bishop to expand on the queenside with a3 and b4.}) 4. Be2 {White ignores Black's move and continues with the intended development of the kingside.} cxd4 ({With this capture Black clarifies the position in the centre. Note that after} 4... d5 {we have a transposition to the lines analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1], arising after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Be2 c5 .}) ({Black can also keep the tension in the centre and play} 4... Nc6 5. O-O Be7 {, but here White employs the rule of thumb to capture on c5 once Black has moved the bishop from f8, thus forcing it to lose time, i.e.} 6. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 7. b3 {followed by Bb2, c4 and Nc3.}) ({If Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop with} 4... b6 {, then White continues with the usual development} 5. O-O Bb7 6. b3 {followed by Bb2 and c4.}) 5. exd4 {White's recapture is governed by the rule of thumb that White always recaptures with a piece when b3 has been played (because the bishop will come out to b2 and it needs an open long diagonal) but without b3 then a capture with a pawn is preferable since the bishop is now free to be developed along the c1-h6 diagonal.} d5 {The most common move that Black can only avoid if they are willing to play a position when that pawn moves only one square forward to d6. In this type of position White obtains free play.} ({For example} 5... Nc6 6. O-O Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 b6 9. h3 {( preparing the development of the bishop to f4, so if attacked by a knight after ...Nh5 it can drop back safely to h2 )} d6 10. Bf4 {followed by Bd3 and Nbd2 with excellent development.}) 6. O-O {White finishes the development of the kingside.} Nc6 {Black can start with the development of the dark-squared bishop first, but for the sake of simplicity we will make the move 6...Nc6 first (since it's going to be played inevitably) and then explore the two possibilities of the bishop development on the next move.} 7. c3 {White connects the pawn structure on the queenside, thus reaching the reversed Carlsbad structure, already discussed [/variation/44724141/#/6/w] in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 in the variation StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O cxd4 . ( The difference with that position is that here Black has played ...e6, which means that they cannot develop the light-squared bishop on a more active square, thus making it a 'bad' bishop, limited in its mobility. White's plan is to develop their pieces in the following manner: Bd3, Re1, Bf4(g5), Nbd2-f1-g3, concentrating their forces on the kingside and intending to plant a knight on the central square e5 with Ne5 and then creating threats against Black's king, which will be castled on the kingside by that time. For an illustration of this plan take a look at the model game Van Dommelen-Van den Oord [/variation/44740513]. Now Black needs to decide where to develop the dark-squared bishop and this will be an indication of their plans: if the bishop is developed on e7 then Black will concentrate on pawn expansion on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5, while if the bishop is developed on d6, then Black will concentrate on an advance in the centre with ...e5.)} Be7 {A more modest development of the bishop. Black wants to castle and then start an attack on the queenside with their pawn, a so-called minority attack.} 8. Bd3 {White improves the position of the light-squared bishop. From the d3-square, it looks towards Black's kingside.} O-O 9. Re1 {The rook belongs on a file where it can be active, in this case from the e1-square. From the e-file the rook controls the e5-square, a good landing spot for the knight on f3.} a6 {Black prepares the advance of the b-pawn. Ideally, Black would like to advance it all the way to the b4-square, to attack the white pawn on c3. This type of advance is called the minority attack, when Black's two pawns (a and b) attack White's three pawns (a, b and c).} 10. Bg5 {White develops the bishop on an active square. They want to follow up with Nbd2, in which case the bishop won't be stuck on its initial square.} b5 ({If Black attacks White's bishop with the move} 10... h6 {, White simply retreats to h4 with} 11. Bh4 {, when little has changed.}) {Black follows the plan of queenside expansion.} 11. Nbd2 {White completes the development of the pieces. Generally speaking, White has two plans in positions similar to this one. One is to play in the centre and the kingside with the help of moves like Ne5, the advance of the h-pawn as far as possible, the rook lift Re3-g3(h3) and so on. We outlined this plan above, in the comment to White's 7th move. However, there is also another plan, and that one is to play on the queenside with the help of the moves b4 and Nb3, targeting the hole on c5, since Black can no longer defend that square with a pawn and landing a knight on that square would be ideal for White. In this concrete position, White should go for the latter plan since it's the easier one to achieve.} Bb7 ({If Black pushes the pawn immediately with} 11... b4 {then after} 12. Rc1 {in case of an exchange of pawns, White will recapture on c3 with the rook and use the c-file to his advantage, aided by the advance of their pawns on the queenside with a3 and b4, with the knight transfer to the c5-square with Nb3-c5 still on the cards.}) 12. b4 $1 {With this move White kills off Black's intended expansion on the queenside, fixes the weak square on c5 and plans the knight maneuver Nb3-c5. Black cannot stop the knight from coming to c5.} Z0 ({For example after} 12... a5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. a3 {the pawn on b5 is attacked and if Black defends it with} Qb6 {then} 15. Nb3 {followed by Nc5 gives White a wonderful knight on c5.}) *

