1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} e6 {Black stays flexible in the centre by not playing ...d5. Here we will examine the lines where Black avoids this move initially, since playing it will inevitably lead to a transposition to the positions we explored in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1].} 3. e3 {Black's development doesn't affect White's, who continues with the standard set-up of Be2 and O-O.} c5 ({Apart from} 3... b6 {, the other moves are not very critical (or very good. )}) ({For example} 3... Be7 {doesn't alter White's plans as they continue with} 4. Be2 {and O-O, when play will likely transpose to the other lines after Black plays ...d5 or ...c5 in the centre.}) ({Giving a check with} 3... Bb4+ $6 {only forces White to play a move that is part of the plan with} 4. Nbd2 {when White can later use the exposed position of the bishop to expand on the queenside with a3 and b4.}) 4. Be2 {White ignores Black's move and continues with the intended development of the kingside.} cxd4 ({With this capture Black clarifies the position in the centre. Note that after} 4... d5 {we have a transposition to the lines analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1], arising after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Be2 c5 .}) ({Black can also keep the tension in the centre and play} 4... Nc6 5. O-O Be7 {, but here White employs the rule of thumb to capture on c5 once Black has moved the bishop from f8, thus forcing it to lose time, i.e.} 6. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 7. b3 {followed by Bb2, c4 and Nc3.}) ({If Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop with} 4... b6 {, then White continues with the usual development} 5. O-O Bb7 6. b3 {followed by Bb2 and c4.}) 5. exd4 {White's recapture is governed by the rule of thumb that White always recaptures with a piece when b3 has been played (because the bishop will come out to b2 and it needs an open long diagonal) but without b3 then a capture with a pawn is preferable since the bishop is now free to be developed along the c1-h6 diagonal.} d5 {The most common move that Black can only avoid if they are willing to play a position when that pawn moves only one square forward to d6. In this type of position White obtains free play.} ({For example} 5... Nc6 6. O-O Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 b6 9. h3 {( preparing the development of the bishop to f4, so if attacked by a knight after ...Nh5 it can drop back safely to h2 )} d6 10. Bf4 {followed by Bd3 and Nbd2 with excellent development.}) 6. O-O {White finishes the development of the kingside.} Nc6 {Black can start with the development of the dark-squared bishop first, but for the sake of simplicity we will make the move 6...Nc6 first (since it's going to be played inevitably) and then explore the two possibilities of the bishop development on the next move.} 7. c3 {White connects the pawn structure on the queenside, thus reaching the reversed Carlsbad structure, already discussed [/variation/44724141/#/6/w] in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 in the variation StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O cxd4 . ( The difference with that position is that here Black has played ...e6, which means that they cannot develop the light-squared bishop on a more active square, thus making it a 'bad' bishop, limited in its mobility. White's plan is to develop their pieces in the following manner: Bd3, Re1, Bf4(g5), Nbd2-f1-g3, concentrating their forces on the kingside and intending to plant a knight on the central square e5 with Ne5 and then creating threats against Black's king, which will be castled on the kingside by that time. For an illustration of this plan take a look at the model game Van Dommelen-Van den Oord [/variation/44740513]. Now Black needs to decide where to develop the dark-squared bishop and this will be an indication of their plans: if the bishop is developed on e7 then Black will concentrate on pawn expansion on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5, while if the bishop is developed on d6, then Black will concentrate on an advance in the centre with ...e5.)} Bd6 {The bishop controls the central e5-square, so Black will try to execute the advance ...e5.} 8. Bd3 {) White continues in the same manner as in the line after 7...Be7. First they improve the activity of the bishop and then the rook will occupy the semi-open e-file.} O-O 9. Re1 {White's plan of development is the same: the dark-squared bishop will be developed on g5 and the queen's knight will come to d2.} Re8 {Black supports the central advance with the rook. It's possible to do so with the queen as well.} ({For example} 9... Qc7 {when White will play} 10. Bg5 {threatening to capture the knight and force the doubling of Black's pawns. There is a funny line that has been played quite a bit which goes} Ng4 $2 11. h3 Nh2 $2 {but the simple} 12. Nfd2 {leaves the knight on h2 stranded forever, which means that sooner or later that knight will be lost.}) 10. Bg5 {White develops the bishop on an active square, from where it pins the knight on f6.} h6 ({If Black advances in the centre play will develop by analogy with the line after} 10... h6 {,}) ({i.e.} 10... e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Nd2 {when White's plan is to establish control over the blockading square d4 with the maneuver Nf3-d4.}) 11. Bh4 {White keeps the bishop on the active diagonal.} e5 {Black doesn't have another active plan with all their pieces concentrated on the central advance. Now the threat is to advance further and attack the bishop and the knight at the same time (a so-called fork) so White should capture the central pawn.} 12. dxe5 {It's also possible to start capturing with the knight,} ({i.e.} 12. Nxe5 {, which after the exchanges will lead to the same position after} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 {.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 {White captures the active knight.} Bxe5 14. Nd2 {Now White has two main ideas at their disposal. One is the afore-mentioned maneuver Nf3-d4 (alternatively Nb3-d4) when the knight is beautifully centralised in front of the isolated pawn on d5. The second idea is the move Bg3, to exchange Black's active bishop, which also controls the important blockading square d4. With this exchange White will exchange an active piece of the opponent and increase the control of the d4-square, again intending Nf3(b3)-d4.} *

