1. d4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will examine Black's plans where they avoid the move ...d5, at least in the initial phase.} 2. Nf3 {For White the plan remains the same: first develop the kingside with e3, Be2 and O-O and then either b3 and Bb2, or c4 and Nc3, depending on Black's set-up.} g6 {Black wants to develop the bishop to g7, the so-called fianchetto. Two moves would lead to positions that are examined elsewhere:} ({the move} 2... c5 {after} 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 d5 5. Be2 Nc6 6. O-O {transposes [/variation/44724141/#/6/w] to the line analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 after the moves StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 Nc6 5.O-O cxd4 6.exd4 .}) ({While the move} 2... Nc6 {(the so-called Two Knights Tango) after} 3. e3 d5 4. Be2 {is analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1] after the moves StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 4.Be2 .}) 3. e3 {White's plan remains the same, so they prepare short castle.} Bg7 4. Be2 {Preparing castling.} O-O 5. O-O {White finished the development of the kingside and now is ready for the second phase of b3 and Bb2.} d6 {This move is the King's Indian approach and is by far the most popular move as the King's Indian Defence is a very popular opening. Black plans for a central push like ...e5 or ...c5, aided by a knight from d7 or c6.} ({The move} 5... d5 {was analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 via the move order [/variation/44724135/#/5/b] StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 g6 4.Be2 Bg7 5.O-O O-O when the proposed move was 6.b4 , followed by a queenside expansion after Bb2, c4, Nbd2, a4, b5 etc.}) ({Against other moves White continues unperturbed, for example} 5... b6 6. b3 Bb7 7. Bb2 d6 8. c4 {with Nc3 next. The only move that doesn't quite allow White to continue with b3 and Bb2 is}) (5... c5 {, when White should just take the pawn} 6. dxc5 {and then continue with c4 and Nc3, eventually aiming for b3 and Bb2, likely prepared by Qc2 (to defend the knight on c3 in advance as it may become exposed along the long diagonal).}) 6. b3 {White follows the plan, which is to continue with Bb2 and then c4.} Nc6 {This is another way for Black to prepare ...e5, but similarly to the lines after} (6... Nbd7 {, after White's next natural and planned move, the execution of ...e5 is anything but easy.}) 7. Bb2 {White plays the intended move and increases the control over the e5-square. In addition to this control, White placed the bishop on the long diagonal to neutralize Black's bishop on g7, so the threat now is to push d5 and attack the knight on c6, without fearing problems with the rook on a1 as after 7.d5? Nxd5! 8.Qxd5 Bxa1 and White loses the rook on a1.} Bg4 {This is a developing move for Black, but after the rule of thumb to play h3 when the bishop appears on g4 White gains the two bishops:} 8. h3 $1 {Attacking the bishop.} Bxf3 9. Bxf3 {White not only obtained the two bishops, but also obtained a strong unopposed light-squared bishop on the long diagonal. White would like to continue with c4 and Nc3. Now the most commonly-played move for Black is a mistake.} e5 $2 {Which simply loses a pawn.} 10. dxe5 {White naturally captures the pawn and now whichever way Black recaptures, they lose a pawn:} Nxe5 ({Or} 10... dxe5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxd8 {( it's useful to exchange queens and enter an endgame with an extra pawn, thus limiting any possible counterplay )} Raxd8 {.}) 11. Bxb7 {White wins a pawn for free.} Rb8 12. Bf3 {The bishop drops to a safe square and White will finish development with Nd2, c4 and so on. If possible, White can also decide to keep the light-squared bishop and drop it back to e2 if Black doesn't capture it.} *

