c5 {, when White should just take the pawn} 6. dxc5 {and then continue with c4 and Nc3, eventually aiming for b3 and Bb2, likely prepared by Qc2 (to defend the knight on c3 in advance as it may become exposed along the long diagonal).}) 6. b3 {White follows the plan, which is to continue with Bb2 and then c4.} Nc6 {This is another way for Black to prepare ...e5, but similarly to the lines after} (6... Nbd7 {, after White's next natural and planned move, the execution of ...e5 is anything but easy.}) 7. Bb2 {White plays the intended move and increases the control over the e5-square. In addition to this control, White placed the bishop on the long diagonal to neutralize Black's bishop on g7, so the threat now is to push d5 and attack the knight on c6, without fearing problems with the rook on a1 as after 7.d5? Nxd5! 8.Qxd5 Bxa1 and White loses the rook on a1.} Re8 {By placing the rook on e8, Black defends the e5-pawn in advance.} 8. d5 $1 {) A fine disruptive move for White, taking advantage of the fact that the knight on c6 is attacked, so White gains space by advancing in the centre. Now wherever the knight retreats, White will continue with the usual moves c4 and Nc3.} Nb8 9. c4 {According to the plan. Now, the last thing White needs to know about this position is that whenever Black pushes the e-pawn, White should recapture en passant with dxe6.} e5 10. dxe6 $1 {This capture ensures that the white bishop on b2 has the long diagonal open.} Bxe6 11. Nc3 {White has smooth development with excellent central control. The next moves will be Nd4 (to harass and ideally capture the bishop on e6), Qd2 and/or Nd5, planting a knight on d5, when the rooks will be developed on d1 and c1.} *

