c5 {, when White should just take the pawn} 6. dxc5 {and then continue with c4 and Nc3, eventually aiming for b3 and Bb2, likely prepared by Qc2 (to defend the knight on c3 in advance as it may become exposed along the long diagonal).}) 6. b3 {White follows the plan, which is to continue with Bb2 and then c4.} Nc6 {This is another way for Black to prepare ...e5, but similarly to the lines after} (6... Nbd7 {, after White's next natural and planned move, the execution of ...e5 is anything but easy.}) 7. Bb2 {White plays the intended move and increases the control over the e5-square. In addition to this control, White placed the bishop on the long diagonal to neutralize Black's bishop on g7, so the threat now is to push d5 and attack the knight on c6, without fearing problems with the rook on a1 as after 7.d5? Nxd5! 8.Qxd5 Bxa1 and White loses the rook on a1.} e5 {Black executes the central advance, but they must be precise on the next move.} 8. dxe5 {) White naturally captures the pawn.} dxe5 $2 {The most commonly-played move is a big mistake! The second most commonly played move is also a mistake.} ({After} 8... Nxe5 $2 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bxe5 {White simply wins a pawn, landing in the same position as after the text move.}) ({Black's best is} 8... Ng4 {which after} 9. c4 Ngxe5 10. Nc3 {leads to a comfortable position for White, who has excellent control of the d5-square and the straight-forward play of Qd2 (to defend the bishop on b2) followed by Nd5, centralising the knight, which is difficult to chase away.}) (8... Nd7 9. c4 Ndxe5 {leads to the same position. Take a look at the model game Grischuk-Vachier [/variation/44740510] to see how White smoothly develops the initiative with natural moves.}) 9. Qxd8 {White first exchanges queens and then collects the free pawn on e5.} Rxd8 10. Nxe5 {White will remain a pawn up.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 {The pawn on c7 is also under attack now, while at the same time, White wants to develop with c4 and Nc3, with a clear extra pawn.} *

