1. Nf3 g6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nbd2 d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. b4 c6 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O {Via a different move order we reached the position from the theoretical chapter.} Bf5 8. c4 {White starts the queenside expansion as explained in the theoretical chapter.} Ne4 {Black threatens ...Nc3.} 9. Bb2 {White develops with the planned developing move, at the same time preventing Black's threat.} Nd7 10. Nxe4 {It's important to note that in this position the exchanges don't make Black's life easier because White's plan of queenside expansion works just as well with fewer pieces on the board.} Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bf5 12. Qb3 {White continues with the intended plan.} Nf6 13. b5 {It was also possible to start with a4. White has an apparent attack on the queenside, while Black can only defend and bank on the solidity of his position.} Ne4 {Black seeks further exchanges, but as explained, this doesn't bother White in the least, because the attack on the queenside continues.} 14. Rfd1 {Defending the knight on d2.} dxc4 15. Nxc4 {The knight is well-placed on c4. White's plan now is to continue with a4 and Ba3, further improving the position on the queenside.} Be6 {Black pins the knight on c4.} 16. a4 {White continues with the plan.} Qd5 17. bxc6 {This exchange is part of White's plan. Ideally, White wants Black to recapture with a pawn, when that pawn on c6 would be isolated and weak.} bxc6 ({Black could have recaptured with a queen, though in that case after} 17... Qxc6 18. Qb5 {White continues with the attack on the queenside, planning Ba3, Rab1, targeting the pawn on b7.}) 18. Qc2 {White avoids the pin by removing the queen from the vulnerable spot and now plans to attack the pawn on c6.} Rab8 19. Ba3 {Continuing the improvement of the pieces. Now the pawn on e7 is hanging.} Rfe8 {Black defends the pawn.} 20. f3 $6 {White wants to remove the knight from e4 , though it was better to do so without the weakening of the pawn structure with 20.Bd3 Nd6 21.Nd2 , with ideas like Rac1, Bc5 etc. when Black is under pressure on the queenside.} Nd6 21. e4 $6 {This looks promising, as the queen is attacked and if it moves then Black loses a pawn when White captures twice on d6, but Black has a good combination at his disposal.} ({It was better to avoid what happened in the game with} 21. Rac1 {, when White keeps good control of the position.}) 21... Qxd4+ $1 {A nice queen sacrifice.} 22. Kh1 Qxa1 23. Rxa1 Bxa1 24. Nxd6 exd6 25. Bxd6 {Black has two rooks for a queen and excellent play.} Rb2 26. Qd1 Bb3 $2 {Black errs. It was better to defend the bishop on a1 with ( 26...Ra2 .} 27. Qxa1 Rxe2 28. h3 {Opening an escape square for the king on h2. Black is in trouble now because White has the simple plan of Qf6 and Be5 with mating threats on the long diagonal.} Rd2 29. Qf6 Rd1+ 30. Kh2 h5 31. Be5 {Black must give up the rook to avoid mate and after that White has a decisive material advantage: the queen is too strong.} Rxe5 32. Qxe5 {The queen can easily pick up weaknesses and play on the dark squares, which is a problem for Black who has a light-squared bishop.} Bxa4 33. Qb8+ Kg7 34. Qxa7 Bb5 35. Kg3 {White will seek to penetrate Black's position along the dark squares and there is little Black can do about it.} Rd2 36. Qe3 Re2 37. Qc3+ Kg8 38. h4 {Fixing the g5-square.} Ra2 39. Qc1 Ra4 40. Kf4 {The king advances.} Rc4 41. Qd2 Rc5 {Black tries to defend by controlling the fifth rank, but this is short-lived after White's next move.} 42. Qd6 {Now the rook cannot stay on the fifth rank.} Rc4 43. Kg5 {Threatening either Kf6 or Kh6.} Rc2 44. g3 {Possible, but White could have forced mate after 44.Kh6.} Kg7 45. Qf6+ Kf8 46. Qd8+ Kg7 47. Qf6+ Kf8 48. Kh6 {Finally entering Black's position.} Rd2 49. Qh8+ Ke7 50. Qe5+ Kf8 51. Qc5+ Kg8 52. Qa7 Rd8 53. Qe7 Ra8 54. Qf6 {From here, White mates or wins a rook.} Kf8 55. Qh8+ Ke7 56. Qxa8 1-0

