1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 Nc6 7. Bb2 e5 8. dxe5 Ng4 {Vachier plays the correct move instead of capturing on e5, which would lead to the loss of a pawn, as we saw in the theoretical part of the course.} 9. c4 Ngxe5 10. Nc3 {White's aim is to plant a knight on the d5-square.} Re8 11. Qd2 ({White must first defend the bishop on b2 before playing Nd5 because the immediate} 11. Nd5 $2 {would lose the bishop after} Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Bxb2 {.}) 11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 {White avoids the exchange of the bishop and has a stable advantage here thanks to the better central control, the d5-square in particular and Black's absence of constructive plans.} Be6 {A developing move, but one without a clear idea.} 14. Rac1 ({White strengthens the position by improving the placement of the rooks. A good alternative is the standard move} 14. Nd5 {, provoking Black to chase away the knight with} c6 {after which} 15. Nf4 {followed by Rfd1 would give White big pressure on the weak pawn on d6. This is the scenario White is looking for when placing a knight on d5.}) 14... Nd7 15. Bf3 {The black knight abandoned the e5-square, from where it controlled the f3-square, so the bishop returns to the long diagonal.} Rb8 16. Rfd1 {White is completely mobilised.} a6 17. Ne4 ({Possible, though the standard} 17. Nd5 {was a good alternative. White seeks the exchange of the dark-squared bishops because that will weaken the position of the black king, which would lack an important defender of the dark squares around it.}) 17... Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Qe7 19. Qd4 {White centralises the queen, eyeing the a7-square and still intending Nc3-d5.} Red8 20. Nc3 {White can take all the time they need to maneuver with the pieces. The threat of Nd5 is omnipresent.} Ne5 21. Be2 {Obviously, White avoids the exchange ...Nxf3 as after gxf3 their pawn structure on the kingside would be weakened.} Nc6 22. Qd2 Ne5 {A clear sign of the passivity of Black's position. If such a dynamic player like Vachier cannot find active resources, the position must be pretty desperate.} 23. Nd5 {Finally executing the main plan.} Bxd5 {Black cannot stand the knight on d5, so this exchange is forced.} 24. cxd5 {This is another transformation that White actively seeks when a knight lands on d5 and Black captures it. By capturing with the c-pawn White opens the c-file, where the backward pawn on c7 can be subject to an attack.} Rbc8 25. b4 ({The simple plan of doubling (or tripling) the heavy pieces on the c-file after} 25. Rc3 {followed by Rdc1 and possibly Qc2 was a good alternative. With the pawn advance White expands on the queenside.}) 25... Nd7 26. h3 {A useful move, though the advance with a4 was also good.} Nf6 27. a4 Kg7 28. a5 {White patiently squeezes Black on the queenside.} Qe8 29. Qd4 {White can play many moves, this is just one of them, centralising the queen and pinning the knight on f6 . The immediate 29.Rc4 was also good.} Qe5 {Black breaks the pin.} 30. Qd3 ({The move} 30. Qa7 {would have been met by 30...Qb2 , when Black gets counterplay, so White keeps the queens on the board.}) 30... h6 31. Rc4 {Finally intending to attack the pawn on c7 by doubling the rooks on the c-file.} Rd7 {Black defends the pawn on c7 in advance.} 32. Rdc1 ({White decides to enter a forcing continuation. It was more technical to squeeze Black some more with} 32. f4 Qe7 33. Bf3 {, covering the pawn on d5, intending e4 and Rdc1, when Black would be left almost without moves.}) 32... Qxd5 33. Qxd5 Nxd5 34. Bg4 $1 {Forcing Black's next move to weaken the seventh rank. The importance of this will be seen later.} f5 35. Bf3 b5 ({The only move to keep Black in the game somehow. If the knight retreats then} 35... Nf6 36. Bxb7 {would win for White as both the pawns on a6 and c7 would fall.}) 36. axb6 Nxb6 37. Rc6 {Now the threat is to take Rxb6 as after the recapture ...cxb6 White wins the rook on c8, remaining a piece up.} Rb8 {Black must give up the extra pawn.} 38. Rxc7 {We see the importance of White's 34th move, which weakened the seventh rank - after the exchange of rooks White recaptures with check, winning time.} Rxc7 39. Rxc7+ Kf6 40. Ra7 $2 ({Alas, in a blitz game one single move ruins all White's excellent efforts up to this point. After the correct} 40. Rb7 $1 Rxb7 41. Bxb7 {White wins the pawn on a6 and has a winning advantage.}) 40... Nc4 $1 {Black is safe now.} 41. Rb7 {One move too late!} Rxb7 42. Bxb7 a5 $1 {The key resource for Black, exchanging White's b-pawn.} 43. Ba6 ({The natural} 43. b5 $2 {would even lose to} Ke6 {when the a-pawn marches down the board.}) 43... d5 44. bxa5 {After the exchange of pawns the endgame is a simple draw.} 1/2-1/2

