1. e4 {The game starts with 1.e4 and the Caro-Kann, but soon we will have a transposition to the lines we analyse in the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6.} c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Be2 e6 {We have reached the position from the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 [/course/276263/5], via the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 cxd4 5.exd4 d5 .} 6. Bf4 {This is a good alternative to placing the bishop on g5, as mentioned in the theoretical part.} Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2 {White develops according to the recommended set-up: the pawn will come to c3, the bishop to d3, the rook to e1 with the idea to plant a knight on e5.} O-O 9. c3 {Connecting the queenside structure.} Bd6 {Black seeks the exchange of the dark-squared bishops even with a loss of tempo. This exchange is favourable for White because Black's dark-squared bishop is the better of the two, so after the exchange Black is left only with the bad light-squared bishop, limited in its mobility by its own pawns.} 10. Bxd6 {White gladly exchanges the bishops.} Qxd6 11. Bd3 {White's moves are understandable and easy; they can be played automatically.} Re8 12. Re1 {The rook comes to the semi-open e-file and controls the e5-square.} Ne7 {Black transfers the knight to g6 to bolster the defence of the kingside.} 13. Ne5 {The knight is very powerful on e5.} Ng6 14. Rc1 {This wasn't really necessary, since White's play lies on the kingside. Supporting the knight on e5 with 14.Ndf3 was good, as it also introduces the threat of Ng5, attacking the pawn on f7 twice. White plays this idea on the next move.} ({An interesting idea worth remembering is the exchange} 14. Bxg6 {, which aims to open the h-file. After} hxg6 15. Re3 $1 {White plans Rh3 and then a transfer of the queen to the h-file. This is very difficult to defend against.}) 14... a6 {Black wants to start the minority attack by advancing the b-pawn all the way to b4, but this is too slow - White's attack on the other side of the board is much faster.} 15. Ndf3 {Intending Ng5.} Nd7 {Black wants to exchange the annoying knight on e5.} 16. Qc2 {The exchange of the bishop for the knight on g6 was still strong, 16.Bxg6 hxg6 17.Re3 with the same idea to transfer the rook to the h-file after exchanging the knights on d7 and placing the knight on f3 to e5.} b5 17. Re3 ({Only now White implements the idea of the rook lift. He also had a tactical solution at his disposal, i.e.} 17. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 18. Ng5+ Kg8 19. Bxg6 hxg6 20. Qxg6 Nf6 21. Qf7+ Kh8 22. Re3 {with a winning attack.}) 17... f5 {Black desperately tries to shut down the access to his kingside, especially along the b1-h7 diagonal, but this only leads to weakening on the e-file.} 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Nh4 {This is fine, though the simple doubling on the e-file was quite good, too.} e5 {Defending the pawn on g6.} 20. dxe5 Rxe5 21. Rce1 {White wins the battle for the e-file.} Bb7 {Missing White's tactical shot. It was better to capture on e3, though after} (21... Rxe3 22. Rxe3 {White dominates the e-file.}) 22. Nxg6 $1 {A pretty combination.} Rxe3 ({In case of} 22... Qxg6 23. Rxe5 Nxe5 24. Rxe5 {White will also win the pawn on f5.}) 23. Rxe3 Qxg6 24. Bxf5 {With the diagonals and files open, all three White pieces will be attacking the black king.} Qc6 {Black defends the knight, but now the king is left defenceless.} 25. Be6+ Kf8 26. Qg6 {Threatening mate.} Ne5 27. Rxe5 {White is two pawns up and has a mating attack, so Black resigned.} 1-0

