1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} Nc6 {A provocative move, luring White to push the d-pawn forward. While the move is definitely good, there is no need for White to play into Black's hands, especially as the trusted mode of development works well here, too.} 2. Nf3 {)} ({Now with the e5-square under control of the knight on f3, the threat is to push d5 since the black knight can no longer use the e5-square to escape. Black was hoping for} 2. d5 Ne5 {, inviting a less explored position.}) 2... d5 {Black should stop White's threat of d5.} ({After} 2... Nf6 $6 3. d5 {the knight is forced to go back to b8, giving White time to expand and develop after} Nb8 4. c4 {with Nc3 and e4 to come.}) 3. e3 {Now we have a transposition to the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1] after the moves StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.e3 .} *

