1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} e6 {A flexible move for Black that allows for various transpositions and in all likelihood the game will transpose to the lines already analysed in the other chapters.} 2. Nf3 {White is unaffected and continues with the usual development. The next moves will be e3 and Be2, preparing short castling.} b6 ({Even this move won't have independent value. After} 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Be2 {play transposes to the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1] via the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Be2}) ({or} 2... c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Be2 d5 6. O-O Nf6 7. c3 {, which is analysed in the chapter Black plays 1...Nf6 [/course/276263/5] via the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 c5 4.Be2 cxd4 5.exd4 d5 6.O-O Nc6 7.c3}) ({or} 2... Nf6 3. e3 {which is a direct transposition to the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 .}) 3. e3 {Continuing the plan.} Bb7 4. Be2 {Intending to castle short. Now Black has to decide what to do in the centre, but they cannot avoid the development of the knight to f6, which would transpose to the variations analysed in the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6.} Nf6 ({The move} 4... f5 5. O-O Nf6 6. c4 {would transpose to the Dutch Defence analysed in this chapter after the moves StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1EndFEN 1...f5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 4.Be2 Be7 5.O-O O-O 6.c4 b6 7.Nc3 Bb7 .}) 5. O-O {And we transposed [/variation/44740756/#/5/w] to the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 via the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 b6 4.Be2 Bb7 5.O-O .} *

