1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} g6 {Black prepares the development of the bishop on g7 and stays flexible with the knight on g8. This gives them some additional possibilities as the unobstructed bishop from g7 can support an early advance with ...e5.} 2. Nf3 {White develops along the standard lines.} Bg7 3. e3 {Intending Be2 and O-O.} d6 {Black's plan in these set-ups is to delay the development of the knight on g8 and execute the central advance ...e5 with the aid of ...Nd7.} 4. Be2 Nd7 {Note that if Black plays the natural ...Nf6 at any point, then we would transpose to the King's Indian from the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 [/course/276263/5] via the move-order 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Be2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.b3.} ({The immediate} 4... e5 $6 {is premature because after} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. O-O {followed by b4, a4 and an expansion on the queenside White has a serious initiative.}) 5. O-O {White completes development.} e5 ({Again in case of} 5... Ngf6 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 {, we have a transposition to the King's Indian from the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 and the move order StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.e3 Bg7 4.Be2 O-O 5.O-O d6 6.b3 Nbd7 7.Bb2 . Now Black threatens to advance with the e-pawn further and possibly defend that pawn by advancing the f-pawn.}) 6. dxe5 {A rare case where White doesn't follow up with c4 or b3 and Bb2. The reason is a prophylactic one, where White wants to prevent Black's plan of ...e4 and possibly ...f5. By changing the structure in the centre White stops Black's further advance.} dxe5 ({This is the better recapture, although the inferior} 6... Nxe5 $6 {is played more often. In that case after} 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 8. e4 {followed by Nc3, Bc4 White obtains excellent placement of their pieces, with control of the d5-square in addition to the space advantage provided by the pawn on e4.}) 7. e4 {This is White's idea. The e-pawn advances and stops Black from doing the same. White's plan of development now is to play Nc3 (to defend the pawn on e4), Bc4 (to place the bishop on an active diagonal), play a4 (to stop Black from expanding with ...b5) with further ideas of a5 (grabbing more queenside space), b3 and Ba3 (activating the dark-squared bishop along the a3-f8 diagonal).} Z0 ({A sample line is} 7... Ngf6 8. Nc3 {(defending the pawn on e4)} O-O 9. Bc4 {(activating the bishop)} c6 10. a4 {(stopping Black's idea of ...b5)} Qc7 11. b3 {with the idea to activate the bishop by placing it on a3, from where it targets the d6-square on the a3-f8 diagonal.}) *

