1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} f5 {This move characterises the Dutch Defence.} 2. Nf3 {White continues with the usual development.} Nf6 3. e3 {White will play Be2 and O-O and then depending on Black's set-up will play b3 or b4 and c4, with the general idea to expand on the queenside. Now Black has to decide which set-up to choose. There are three possible set-ups for Black: the Leningrad Dutch with 3...g6, the Stonewall Dutch with ...e6 and ...d5 and the Classical Dutch where Black can play ...b6 and ...Bb7 or ...d6 and ...e5.} g6 {This move is characteristic of the Leningrad Dutch, where Black wants to develop the bishop to g7 and castle short.} 4. Be2 {White continues with the usual development.} Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. b4 ({White can be more ambitious here compared to the more common} 6. b3 {because Black is not stopping the queenside expansion. The plan is to advance on the queenside with Bb2, c4, Nc3 or Nbd2 and so on.}) 6... d6 7. Bb2 {Controlling the e5-square.} Qe8 {Black's main plan is to execute the ...e5 push, but that is not easy.} 8. c4 {White continues the expansion.} Nbd7 {Preparing ...e5.} 9. Nc3 {The knight is more active on c3, from where it can go to both b5 and d5, targeting the pawn on c7.} e5 $2 {This is very common, but it loses.} 10. Nb5 {Attacking the pawn on c7.} Qd8 {The only way to defend the pawn, but now the pawn on e5 is without protection.} 11. dxe5 {Ensuring that White obtains material advantage.} dxe5 12. Nxe5 ({Wins a pawn, though} 12. Ng5 {is even stronger, threatening Ne6.}) *

