1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} f5 {This move characterises the Dutch Defence.} 2. Nf3 {White continues with the usual development.} Nf6 3. e3 {White will play Be2 and O-O and then depending on Black's set-up will play b3 or b4 and c4, with the general idea to expand on the queenside. Now Black has to decide which set-up to choose. There are three possible set-ups for Black: the Leningrad Dutch with 3...g6, the Stonewall Dutch with ...e6 and ...d5 and the Classical Dutch where Black can play ...b6 and ...Bb7 or ...d6 and ...e5.} e6 {Black can further decide whether to play ...d6 or ...d5.} 4. Be2 {White develops in the usual way.} d5 {This pawn formation, of black pawns on f5, e6, d5 and later c6 is called the Stonewall formation as it is rock solid. Black banks on the control of the light squares, but on the other hand weakens the central e5-square. Thus, White's plan is to exchange the dark-squared bishops and weaken Black's control over that square.} 5. O-O {First White finishes the development of the kingside as planned.} Bd6 6. c4 {Then the central advance with the c-pawn follows, to get some space on the queenside.} c6 {Black strengthens the centre and obtains the desired Stonewall formation.} 7. b3 $1 {White doesn't rush with the development of the knight on c3 because the knight is needed to support the bishop's sortie to a3.} O-O ({Black castles and now White achieves the aim of exchanging the dark-squared bishops. Black couldn't stop that even if they wanted to because after} 7... Qe7 8. a4 $1 {the rook from a1 helps control the a3-square where the bishop should come to, hence making the next move Ba3 inevitable, with the ensuing exchange of the dark-squared bishops.}) 8. Ba3 {White achieves their goal.} Bxa3 9. Nxa3 {White has the straightforward plan to occupy the e5-square with the maneuver Nc2-e1-d3, when the knight from f3 will jump to the e5-square. White will combine this control of the e5-square with the move f3 (to control the e4-square so that a black knight cannot establish itself there) with a further advance on the queenside with b4-b5, a4, possibly c5 and so on.} *

