1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} f5 {This move characterises the Dutch Defence.} 2. Nf3 {White continues with the usual development.} Nf6 3. e3 {White will play Be2 and O-O and then depending on Black's set-up will play b3 or b4 and c4, with the general idea to expand on the queenside. Now Black has to decide which set-up to choose. There are three possible set-ups for Black: the Leningrad Dutch with 3...g6, the Stonewall Dutch with ...e6 and ...d5 and the Classical Dutch where Black can play ...b6 and ...Bb7 or ...d6 and ...e5.} e6 {Black can further decide whether to play ...d6 or ...d5.} 4. Be2 {White develops in the usual way.} Be7 {This is the classical development.} 5. O-O {White continues with the natural development.} O-O {And so does Black.} 6. c4 {White expands in the centre. After the c-pawn move the developing move Nc3 can follow.} b6 ({The more popular way of developing. In case of} 6... d6 7. Nc3 Qe8 {(Black intends either ...Qg6 or ...Bd8 and ...e5)} 8. b4 {White advances on the queenside and has two ways to deal with Black's main ideas: against ...Qg6 the maneuver Ne1-d3 is important to allow for f3 or f4 to stop any attack Black may create on the kingside. While after ...Bd8, White develops with Bb2 and when Black plays ...e5 White captures on e5 with the pawn dxe5 and then continues with the queenside advance with b5, a4 and so on, always keeping in mind the knight jump Nd5.}) 7. Nc3 {White plays the intended developing move.} Bb7 {Black develops the bishop on the long diagonal. Now White's next move is very important, if somewhat unexpected.} 8. Ng5 $1 {The move may seem senseless because the knight is not attacking anything, but in fact, it is the first step towards a regrouping that is aimed against Black's control of the light squares along the long diagonal. White intends to play f3 and then drop the knight back to h3, from where it can go either to f4 or f2. With a pawn on f3, White successfully blunts the black bishop on b7 by controlling the central e4-square.} h6 9. Nh3 {Intending f3.} g5 {This only looks aggressive, while in fact it weakens the black king.} 10. f3 {With the knight coming back to f2 White has a very compact position. There are two plans at their disposal, the central advance e4 and the queenside expansion with a3, b4 and so on.} *

