1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} d6 {Black threatens an immediate advance with the e-pawn with ...e5.} 2. Nf3 {) White's plannned move here has the added benefit of stopping Black's idea to advance in the centre with ...e5.} Bg4 ({A known system at higher levels, though not very popular at lower levels. The other moves would transpose, for example} 2... Nf6 3. e3 {is a transposition to the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 [/course/276263/5] after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 3.e3}) (2... g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 {transposes to the variation after [/variation/44725988/#/4/w] StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1EndFEN 1...g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e3 d6 4.Be2}) 3. e3 {Intending Be2 to continue development. White doesn't play} (3. h3 $6 {here as after} Bxf3 {they would be forced to double their pawns whichever way they decide to recapture the bishop.}) 3... Bxf3 ({The most common move; the others would also transpose. For example the natural} 3... Nf6 4. h3 {leads us to the chapter Black Plays 1...Nf6 after StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 3.e3 Bg4 4.h3 .}) 4. Qxf3 {The natural recapture, targeting the pawn on b7.} c6 {Black blocks the long diagonal and defends the pawn on b7.} 5. c4 {White will continue with development with the moves Nc3, Bd3 and O-O, the bishop being developed on the more active square on d3 so that the queen can drop back to e2 if needed.} *

