1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} b5 {A strange move that characterises the Polish Defence. White can continue with the standard development, only this time starting with the pawn move as it opens the f1-a6 diagonal for the light-squared bishop, thus immediately targeting the exposed pawn on b5.} 2. e3 {White plays a move that is part of the plan, while at the same time attacking the pawn on b5.} Bb7 {Black lures White to take the pawn on b5, in which case the pawn on g2 would remain undefended.} 3. Nf3 {White develops and renews the threat against the pawn on b5 . It would be bad to play 3.Bxb5? Bxg2 when White loses the rook on h1.} a6 {Black defends the pawn on b5.} 4. Be2 {White continues with the usual development.} e6 5. O-O {White's plan remains the same: to play b3, then develop the bishop to b2 and then expand with c4.} c5 6. b3 {Following the plan.} Nf6 ({In case of} 6... cxd4 {the rule of thumb of keeping the long diagonal open for the dark-squared bishop once b3 has been played remains in force:} 7. Nxd4 {followed by Bb2.}) 7. Bb2 {White plays the usual moves.} Be7 {And now the rule of thumb of taking on c5 once Black has moved the bishop from f8 is still valid.} 8. dxc5 {Forcing the bishop to move again.} Bxc5 9. Nbd2 {With c4 to come next and White has achieved smooth development with good central control.} *

