1. d4 {In this chapter we will cover the remaining first moves that Black has at their disposal.} e5 $6 {Curiously enough, this bad move is played very often. This is owed to the fact that against White's most natural moves Black has a tempting trap at their disposal. A lot of the other moves will transpose to the other chapters because Black cannot conveniently avoid the moves ...d5 and ...Nf6, thus leading to the corresponding chapters.} ({For example} 1... c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Be2 {is a transposition to the chapter Black Plays 1...d5 [/course/276263/1] after 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 c6 4.Be2}) ({or} 1... b6 2. Nf3 Bb7 3. e3 e6 4. Be2 {transposes to 1...e6 2.Nf3 b6 3.e3 Bb7 4.Be2 [/variation/44725987/#/4/w].}) 2. dxe5 {White naturally takes the free pawn.} Nc6 {Black attacks the pawn on e5.} 3. Nf3 {White develops with the usual knight move and defends the pawn on e5.} Qe7 {Black attacks the pawn for the second time.} 4. e3 {Spoiling the fun for the opponent is a lot of fun for ourselves. White sticks to the tested way of development, preparing Be2 and O-O.} ({The trap I mentioned is worth knowing and it arises after} 4. Bf4 {(White defends the pawn on e5)} Qb4+ {(check and an attack on the bishop on f4, so White's next move is forced)} 5. Bd2 Qxb2 {the rook on a1 is hanging and if now White plays the most natural move} 6. Bc3 $4 {then after} Bb4 $1 {they are suddenly lost because after} 7. Bxb4 Nxb4 {the rook on a1 is still under attack but the pawn on c2 is also threatened. To avoid all this, the simplest thing is to stick to the usual development as in all the other lines in the course.}) 4... Nxe5 5. Be2 {White continues with the plan.} Nxf3+ ({Black can also play} 5... Nf6 6. O-O d5 {but after} 7. Nbd2 {, connecting the knights and preparing to replace the knight on f3 if Black captures it, White will continue with the standard development with b3 and Bb2 or an immediate attack in the centre with c4.}) 6. Bxf3 {The bishop is well-placed on the long diagonal.} Nf6 {Black should also develop, but the queen on e7 gets in the way of the development of the bishop on f8.} 7. O-O {White's king is secure and now the moves c4, Nc3 and Bb2 will follow, with excellent control of the centre, the outpost on d5 in particular.} *

